68 // Define attributes of all API symbols declarations (e.g. for DLL under Windows)
69 // IMGUI_API is used for core imgui functions, IMGUI_IMPL_API is used for the default backends files (imgui_impl_xxx.h)
70 // Using dear imgui via a shared library is not recommended, because we don't guarantee backward nor forward ABI compatibility (also function call overhead, as dear imgui is a call-heavy API)

83 #define IM_ARRAYSIZE(_ARR) ((int)(sizeof(_ARR) / sizeof(*(_ARR)))) // Size of a static C-style array. Don't use on pointers!
84 #define IM_UNUSED(_VAR) ((void)(_VAR)) // Used to silence "unused variable warnings". Often useful as asserts may be stripped out from final builds.
85 #if (__cplusplus >= 201100) || (defined(_MSVC_LANG) && _MSVC_LANG >= 201100)
86 #define IM_OFFSETOF(_TYPE,_MEMBER) offsetof(_TYPE, _MEMBER) // Offset of _MEMBER within _TYPE. Standardized as offsetof() in C++11
87 #else
88 #define IM_OFFSETOF(_TYPE,_MEMBER) ((size_t)&(((_TYPE*)0)->_MEMBER)) // Offset of _MEMBER within _TYPE. Old style macro.
89 #endif

133 // Forward declarations
134 struct ImDrawChannel; // Temporary storage to output draw commands out of order, used by ImDrawListSplitter and ImDrawList::ChannelsSplit()
135 struct ImDrawCmd; // A single draw command within a parent ImDrawList (generally maps to 1 GPU draw call, unless it is a callback)
136 struct ImDrawData; // All draw command lists required to render the frame + pos/size coordinates to use for the projection matrix.
137 struct ImDrawList; // A single draw command list (generally one per window, conceptually you may see this as a dynamic "mesh" builder)
138 struct ImDrawListSharedData; // Data shared among multiple draw lists (typically owned by parent ImGui context, but you may create one yourself)
139 struct ImDrawListSplitter; // Helper to split a draw list into different layers which can be drawn into out of order, then flattened back.
140 struct ImDrawVert; // A single vertex (pos + uv + col = 20 bytes by default. Override layout with IMGUI_OVERRIDE_DRAWVERT_STRUCT_LAYOUT)
141 struct ImFont; // Runtime data for a single font within a parent ImFontAtlas
142 struct ImFontAtlas; // Runtime data for multiple fonts, bake multiple fonts into a single texture, TTF/OTF font loader
143 struct ImFontBuilderIO; // Opaque interface to a font builder (stb_truetype or FreeType).
144 struct ImFontConfig; // Configuration data when adding a font or merging fonts
145 struct ImFontGlyph; // A single font glyph (code point + coordinates within in ImFontAtlas + offset)
146 struct ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder; // Helper to build glyph ranges from text/string data
147 struct ImColor; // Helper functions to create a color that can be converted to either u32 or float4 (*OBSOLETE* please avoid using)
148 struct ImGuiContext; // Dear ImGui context (opaque structure, unless including imgui_internal.h)
149 struct ImGuiIO; // Main configuration and I/O between your application and ImGui
150 struct ImGuiInputTextCallbackData; // Shared state of InputText() when using custom ImGuiInputTextCallback (rare/advanced use)
151 struct ImGuiListClipper; // Helper to manually clip large list of items
152 struct ImGuiOnceUponAFrame; // Helper for running a block of code not more than once a frame, used by IMGUI_ONCE_UPON_A_FRAME macro
153 struct ImGuiPayload; // User data payload for drag and drop operations
154 struct ImGuiSizeCallbackData; // Callback data when using SetNextWindowSizeConstraints() (rare/advanced use)
155 struct ImGuiStorage; // Helper for key->value storage
156 struct ImGuiStyle; // Runtime data for styling/colors
157 struct ImGuiTableSortSpecs; // Sorting specifications for a table (often handling sort specs for a single column, occasionally more)
158 struct ImGuiTableColumnSortSpecs; // Sorting specification for one column of a table
159 struct ImGuiTextBuffer; // Helper to hold and append into a text buffer (~string builder)
160 struct ImGuiTextFilter; // Helper to parse and apply text filters (e.g. "aaaaa[,bbbbb][,ccccc]")
161 struct ImGuiViewport; // A Platform Window (always only one in 'master' branch), in the future may represent Platform Monitor

203 // ImTexture: user data for renderer backend to identify a texture [Compile-time configurable type]
204 // - To use something else than an opaque void* pointer: override with e.g. '#define ImTextureID MyTextureType*' in your imconfig.h file.
205 // - This can be whatever to you want it to be! read the FAQ about ImTextureID for details.
206 #ifndef ImTextureID
207 typedef void *ImTextureID; // Default: store a pointer or an integer fitting in a pointer (most renderer backends are ok with that)
208 #endif
209 
210 // ImDrawIdx: vertex index. [Compile-time configurable type]
211 // - To use 16-bit indices + allow large meshes: backend need to set 'io.BackendFlags |= ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasVtxOffset' and handle ImDrawCmd::VtxOffset (recommended).
212 // - To use 32-bit indices: override with '#define ImDrawIdx unsigned int' in your imconfig.h file.
213 #ifndef ImDrawIdx
214 typedef unsigned short ImDrawIdx; // Default: 16-bit (for maximum compatibility with renderer backends)
215 #endif

217 // Scalar data types
218 typedef unsigned int ImGuiID;// A unique ID used by widgets (typically the result of hashing a stack of string)
219 typedef signed char ImS8; // 8-bit signed integer
220 typedef unsigned char ImU8; // 8-bit unsigned integer
221 typedef signed short ImS16; // 16-bit signed integer
222 typedef unsigned short ImU16; // 16-bit unsigned integer
223 typedef signed int ImS32; // 32-bit signed integer == int
224 typedef unsigned int ImU32; // 32-bit unsigned integer (often used to store packed colors)
225 #if defined(_MSC_VER) && !defined(__clang__)
226 typedef signed __int64 ImS64; // 64-bit signed integer (pre and post C++11 with Visual Studio)
227 typedef unsigned __int64 ImU64; // 64-bit unsigned integer (pre and post C++11 with Visual Studio)
228 #elif (defined(__clang__) || defined(__GNUC__)) && (__cplusplus < 201100)
229 #include <stdint.h>
230 typedef int64_t ImS64; // 64-bit signed integer (pre C++11)
231 typedef uint64_t ImU64; // 64-bit unsigned integer (pre C++11)
232 #else
233 typedef signed long long ImS64; // 64-bit signed integer (post C++11)
234 typedef unsigned long long ImU64; // 64-bit unsigned integer (post C++11)
235 #endif

237 // Character types
238 // (we generally use UTF-8 encoded string in the API. This is storage specifically for a decoded character used for keyboard input and display)
239 typedef unsigned short ImWchar16; // A single decoded U16 character/code point. We encode them as multi bytes UTF-8 when used in strings.
240 typedef unsigned int ImWchar32; // A single decoded U32 character/code point. We encode them as multi bytes UTF-8 when used in strings.
241 #ifdef IMGUI_USE_WCHAR32 // ImWchar [configurable type: override in imconfig.h with '#define IMGUI_USE_WCHAR32' to support Unicode planes 1-16]
242 typedef ImWchar32 ImWchar;
243 #else
244 typedef ImWchar16 ImWchar;
245 #endif

253 // ImVec2: 2D vector used to store positions, sizes etc. [Compile-time configurable type]
254 // This is a frequently used type in the API. Consider using IM_VEC2_CLASS_EXTRA to create implicit cast from/to our preferred type.
255 IM_MSVC_RUNTIME_CHECKS_OFF
256 struct ImVec2
257 {
258  float x, y;
259  ImVec2()
260  {
261  x = y = 0.0f;
262  }
263  ImVec2(float _x, float _y)
264  {
265  x = _x; y = _y;
266  }
267  float operator[] (size_t idx) const
268  {
269  IM_ASSERT(idx <= 1); return (&x)[idx];
270  } // We very rarely use this [] operator, the assert overhead is fine.
271  float &operator[] (size_t idx)
272  {
273  IM_ASSERT(idx <= 1); return (&x)[idx];
274  } // We very rarely use this [] operator, the assert overhead is fine.
275 #ifdef IM_VEC2_CLASS_EXTRA
276  IM_VEC2_CLASS_EXTRA // Define additional constructors and implicit cast operators in imconfig.h to convert back and forth between your math types and ImVec2.
277 #endif
278 };
279 
280 // ImVec4: 4D vector used to store clipping rectangles, colors etc. [Compile-time configurable type]
281 struct ImVec4
282 {
283  float x, y, z, w;
284  ImVec4()
285  {
286  x = y = z = w = 0.0f;
287  }
288  ImVec4(float _x, float _y, float _z, float _w)
289  {
290  x = _x; y = _y; z = _z; w = _w;
291  }
292 #ifdef IM_VEC4_CLASS_EXTRA
293  IM_VEC4_CLASS_EXTRA // Define additional constructors and implicit cast operators in imconfig.h to convert back and forth between your math types and ImVec4.
294 #endif
295 };

305  // Context creation and access
306  // - Each context create its own ImFontAtlas by default. You may instance one yourself and pass it to CreateContext() to share a font atlas between contexts.
307  // - DLL users: heaps and globals are not shared across DLL boundaries! You will need to call SetCurrentContext() + SetAllocatorFunctions()
308  // for each static/DLL boundary you are calling from. Read "Context and Memory Allocators" section of imgui.cpp for details.
309  IMGUI_API ImGuiContext *CreateContext(ImFontAtlas *shared_font_atlas = NULL);
310  IMGUI_API void DestroyContext(ImGuiContext *ctx = NULL); // NULL = destroy current context

314  // Main
315  IMGUI_API ImGuiIO &GetIO(); // access the IO structure (mouse/keyboard/gamepad inputs, time, various configuration options/flags)
316  IMGUI_API ImGuiStyle &GetStyle(); // access the Style structure (colors, sizes). Always use PushStyleCol(), PushStyleVar() to modify style mid-frame!
317  IMGUI_API void NewFrame(); // start a new Dear ImGui frame, you can submit any command from this point until Render()/EndFrame().
318  IMGUI_API void EndFrame(); // ends the Dear ImGui frame. automatically called by Render(). If you don't need to render data (skipping rendering) you may call EndFrame() without Render()... but you'll have wasted CPU already! If you don't need to render, better to not create any windows and not call NewFrame() at all!
319  IMGUI_API void Render(); // ends the Dear ImGui frame, finalize the draw data. You can then get call GetDrawData().
320  IMGUI_API ImDrawData *GetDrawData(); // valid after Render() and until the next call to NewFrame(). this is what you have to render.

325  IMGUI_API void ShowAboutWindow(bool *p_open = NULL); // create About window. display Dear ImGui version, credits and build/system information.
326  IMGUI_API void ShowStyleEditor(ImGuiStyle *ref = NULL); // add style editor block (not a window). you can pass in a reference ImGuiStyle structure to compare to, revert to and save to (else it uses the default style)
327  IMGUI_API bool ShowStyleSelector(const char *label); // add style selector block (not a window), essentially a combo listing the default styles.
328  IMGUI_API void ShowFontSelector(const char *label); // add font selector block (not a window), essentially a combo listing the loaded fonts.

337  // Windows
338  // - Begin() = push window to the stack and start appending to it. End() = pop window from the stack.
339  // - Passing 'bool* p_open != NULL' shows a window-closing widget in the upper-right corner of the window,
340  // which clicking will set the boolean to false when clicked.
341  // - You may append multiple times to the same window during the same frame by calling Begin()/End() pairs multiple times.
342  // Some information such as 'flags' or 'p_open' will only be considered by the first call to Begin().
343  // - Begin() return false to indicate the window is collapsed or fully clipped, so you may early out and omit submitting
344  // anything to the window. Always call a matching End() for each Begin() call, regardless of its return value!
345  // [Important: due to legacy reason, this is inconsistent with most other functions such as BeginMenu/EndMenu,
346  // BeginPopup/EndPopup, etc. where the EndXXX call should only be called if the corresponding BeginXXX function
347  // returned true. Begin and BeginChild are the only odd ones out. Will be fixed in a future update.]
348  // - Note that the bottom of window stack always contains a window called "Debug".
349  IMGUI_API bool Begin(const char *name, bool *p_open = NULL, ImGuiWindowFlags flags = 0);
350  IMGUI_API void End();
351 
352  // Child Windows
353  // - Use child windows to begin into a self-contained independent scrolling/clipping regions within a host window. Child windows can embed their own child.
354  // - For each independent axis of 'size': ==0.0f: use remaining host window size / >0.0f: fixed size / <0.0f: use remaining window size minus abs(size) / Each axis can use a different mode, e.g. ImVec2(0,400).
355  // - BeginChild() returns false to indicate the window is collapsed or fully clipped, so you may early out and omit submitting anything to the window.
356  // Always call a matching EndChild() for each BeginChild() call, regardless of its return value.
357  // [Important: due to legacy reason, this is inconsistent with most other functions such as BeginMenu/EndMenu,
358  // BeginPopup/EndPopup, etc. where the EndXXX call should only be called if the corresponding BeginXXX function
359  // returned true. Begin and BeginChild are the only odd ones out. Will be fixed in a future update.]
360  IMGUI_API bool BeginChild(const char *str_id, const ImVec2 &size = ImVec2(0, 0), bool border = false, ImGuiWindowFlags flags = 0);
361  IMGUI_API bool BeginChild(ImGuiID id, const ImVec2 &size = ImVec2(0, 0), bool border = false, ImGuiWindowFlags flags = 0);
362  IMGUI_API void EndChild();
363 
364  // Windows Utilities
365  // - 'current window' = the window we are appending into while inside a Begin()/End() block. 'next window' = next window we will Begin() into.
366  IMGUI_API bool IsWindowAppearing();
367  IMGUI_API bool IsWindowCollapsed();
368  IMGUI_API bool IsWindowFocused(ImGuiFocusedFlags flags = 0); // is current window focused? or its root/child, depending on flags. see flags for options.
369  IMGUI_API bool IsWindowHovered(ImGuiHoveredFlags flags = 0); // is current window hovered (and typically: not blocked by a popup/modal)? see flags for options. NB: If you are trying to check whether your mouse should be dispatched to imgui or to your app, you should use the 'io.WantCaptureMouse' boolean for that! Please read the FAQ!

448  // Cursor / Layout
449  // - By "cursor" we mean the current output position.
450  // - The typical widget behavior is to output themselves at the current cursor position, then move the cursor one line down.
451  // - You can call SameLine() between widgets to undo the last carriage return and output at the right of the preceding widget.
452  // - Attention! We currently have inconsistencies between window-local and absolute positions we will aim to fix with future API:
453  // Window-local coordinates: SameLine(), GetCursorPos(), SetCursorPos(), GetCursorStartPos(), GetContentRegionMax(), GetWindowContentRegion*(), PushTextWrapPos()
454  // Absolute coordinate: GetCursorScreenPos(), SetCursorScreenPos(), all ImDrawList:: functions.
455  IMGUI_API void Separator(); // separator, generally horizontal. inside a menu bar or in horizontal layout mode, this becomes a vertical separator.
456  IMGUI_API void SameLine(float offset_from_start_x = 0.0f, float spacing = -1.0f); // call between widgets or groups to layout them horizontally. X position given in window coordinates.
457  IMGUI_API void NewLine(); // undo a SameLine() or force a new line when in an horizontal-layout context.
458  IMGUI_API void Spacing(); // add vertical spacing.
459  IMGUI_API void Dummy(const ImVec2 &size); // add a dummy item of given size. unlike InvisibleButton(), Dummy() won't take the mouse click or be navigable into.
460  IMGUI_API void Indent(float indent_w = 0.0f); // move content position toward the right, by indent_w, or style.IndentSpacing if indent_w <= 0
461  IMGUI_API void Unindent(float indent_w = 0.0f); // move content position back to the left, by indent_w, or style.IndentSpacing if indent_w <= 0
462  IMGUI_API void BeginGroup(); // lock horizontal starting position
463  IMGUI_API void EndGroup(); // unlock horizontal starting position + capture the whole group bounding box into one "item" (so you can use IsItemHovered() or layout primitives such as SameLine() on whole group, etc.)
464  IMGUI_API ImVec2 GetCursorPos(); // cursor position in window coordinates (relative to window position)

479  // ID stack/scopes
480  // Read the FAQ (docs/FAQ.md or http://dearimgui.org/faq) for more details about how ID are handled in dear imgui.
481  // - Those questions are answered and impacted by understanding of the ID stack system:
482  // - "Q: Why is my widget not reacting when I click on it?"
483  // - "Q: How can I have widgets with an empty label?"
484  // - "Q: How can I have multiple widgets with the same label?"
485  // - Short version: ID are hashes of the entire ID stack. If you are creating widgets in a loop you most likely
486  // want to push a unique identifier (e.g. object pointer, loop index) to uniquely differentiate them.
487  // - You can also use the "Label##foobar" syntax within widget label to distinguish them from each others.
488  // - In this header file we use the "label"/"name" terminology to denote a string that will be displayed + used as an ID,
489  // whereas "str_id" denote a string that is only used as an ID and not normally displayed.
490  IMGUI_API void PushID(const char *str_id); // push string into the ID stack (will hash string).
491  IMGUI_API void PushID(const char *str_id_begin, const char *str_id_end); // push string into the ID stack (will hash string).
492  IMGUI_API void PushID(const void *ptr_id); // push pointer into the ID stack (will hash pointer).
493  IMGUI_API void PushID(int int_id); // push integer into the ID stack (will hash integer).
494  IMGUI_API void PopID(); // pop from the ID stack.
495  IMGUI_API ImGuiID GetID(const char *str_id); // calculate unique ID (hash of whole ID stack + given parameter). e.g. if you want to query into ImGuiStorage yourself
496  IMGUI_API ImGuiID GetID(const char *str_id_begin, const char *str_id_end);
497  IMGUI_API ImGuiID GetID(const void *ptr_id);
498

540  // Widgets: Drag Sliders
541  // - CTRL+Click on any drag box to turn them into an input box. Manually input values aren't clamped and can go off-bounds.
542  // - For all the Float2/Float3/Float4/Int2/Int3/Int4 versions of every functions, note that a 'float v[X]' function argument is the same as 'float* v', the array syntax is just a way to document the number of elements that are expected to be accessible. You can pass address of your first element out of a contiguous set, e.g. &myvector.x
543  // - Adjust format string to decorate the value with a prefix, a suffix, or adapt the editing and display precision e.g. "%.3f" -> 1.234; "%5.2f secs" -> 01.23 secs; "Biscuit: %.0f" -> Biscuit: 1; etc.
544  // - Format string may also be set to NULL or use the default format ("%f" or "%d").
545  // - Speed are per-pixel of mouse movement (v_speed=0.2f: mouse needs to move by 5 pixels to increase value by 1). For gamepad/keyboard navigation, minimum speed is Max(v_speed, minimum_step_at_given_precision).
546  // - Use v_min < v_max to clamp edits to given limits. Note that CTRL+Click manual input can override those limits.
547  // - Use v_max = FLT_MAX / INT_MAX etc to avoid clamping to a maximum, same with v_min = -FLT_MAX / INT_MIN to avoid clamping to a minimum.
548  // - We use the same sets of flags for DragXXX() and SliderXXX() functions as the features are the same and it makes it easier to swap them.
549  // - Legacy: Pre-1.78 there are DragXXX() function signatures that takes a final `float power=1.0f' argument instead of the `ImGuiSliderFlags flags=0' argument.
550  // If you get a warning converting a float to ImGuiSliderFlags, read https://github.com/ocornut/imgui/issues/3361
551  IMGUI_API bool DragFloat(const char *label, float *v, float v_speed = 1.0f, float v_min = 0.0f, float v_max = 0.0f, const char *format = "%.3f", ImGuiSliderFlags flags = 0); // If v_min >= v_max we have no bound
552  IMGUI_API bool DragFloat2(const char *label, float v[2], float v_speed = 1.0f, float v_min = 0.0f, float v_max = 0.0f, const char *format = "%.3f", ImGuiSliderFlags flags = 0);
553  IMGUI_API bool DragFloat3(const char *label, float v[3], float v_speed = 1.0f, float v_min = 0.0f, float v_max = 0.0f, const char *format = "%.3f", ImGuiSliderFlags flags = 0);
554  IMGUI_API bool DragFloat4(const char *label, float v[4], float v_speed = 1.0f, float v_min = 0.0f, float v_max = 0.0f, const char *format = "%.3f", ImGuiSliderFlags flags = 0);
555  IMGUI_API bool DragFloatRange2(const char *label, float *v_current_min, float *v_current_max, float v_speed = 1.0f, float v_min = 0.0f, float v_max = 0.0f, const char *format = "%.3f", const char *format_max = NULL, ImGuiSliderFlags flags = 0);
556  IMGUI_API bool DragInt(const char *label, int *v, float v_speed = 1.0f, int v_min = 0, int v_max = 0, const char *format = "%d", ImGuiSliderFlags flags = 0); // If v_min >= v_max we have no bound
557  IMGUI_API bool DragInt2(const char *label, int v[2], float v_speed = 1.0f, int v_min = 0, int v_max = 0, const char *format = "%d", ImGuiSliderFlags flags = 0);
558  IMGUI_API bool DragInt3(const char *label, int v[3], float v_speed = 1.0f, int v_min = 0, int v_max = 0, const char *format = "%d", ImGuiSliderFlags flags = 0);

561  IMGUI_API bool DragScalar(const char *label, ImGuiDataType data_type, void *p_data, float v_speed = 1.0f, const void *p_min = NULL, const void *p_max = NULL, const char *format = NULL, ImGuiSliderFlags flags = 0);

685  // Popups, Modals
686  // - They block normal mouse hovering detection (and therefore most mouse interactions) behind them.
687  // - If not modal: they can be closed by clicking anywhere outside them, or by pressing ESCAPE.
688  // - Their visibility state (~bool) is held internally instead of being held by the programmer as we are used to with regular Begin*() calls.
689  // - The 3 properties above are related: we need to retain popup visibility state in the library because popups may be closed as any time.
690  // - You can bypass the hovering restriction by using ImGuiHoveredFlags_AllowWhenBlockedByPopup when calling IsItemHovered() or IsWindowHovered().
691  // - IMPORTANT: Popup identifiers are relative to the current ID stack, so OpenPopup and BeginPopup generally needs to be at the same level of the stack.
692  // This is sometimes leading to confusing mistakes. May rework this in the future.
693 
694  // Popups: begin/end functions
695  // - BeginPopup(): query popup state, if open start appending into the window. Call EndPopup() afterwards. ImGuiWindowFlags are forwarded to the window.
696  // - BeginPopupModal(): block every interactions behind the window, cannot be closed by user, add a dimming background, has a title bar.
697  IMGUI_API bool BeginPopup(const char *str_id, ImGuiWindowFlags flags = 0); // return true if the popup is open, and you can start outputting to it.
698  IMGUI_API bool BeginPopupModal(const char *name, bool *p_open = NULL, ImGuiWindowFlags flags = 0); // return true if the modal is open, and you can start outputting to it.
699  IMGUI_API void EndPopup(); // only call EndPopup() if BeginPopupXXX() returns true!
700 
701  // Popups: open/close functions
702  // - OpenPopup(): set popup state to open. ImGuiPopupFlags are available for opening options.
703  // - If not modal: they can be closed by clicking anywhere outside them, or by pressing ESCAPE.
704  // - CloseCurrentPopup(): use inside the BeginPopup()/EndPopup() scope to close manually.
705  // - CloseCurrentPopup() is called by default by Selectable()/MenuItem() when activated (FIXME: need some options).
706  // - Use ImGuiPopupFlags_NoOpenOverExistingPopup to avoid opening a popup if there's already one at the same level. This is equivalent to e.g. testing for !IsAnyPopupOpen() prior to OpenPopup().
707  // - Use IsWindowAppearing() after BeginPopup() to tell if a window just opened.
708  IMGUI_API void OpenPopup(const char *str_id, ImGuiPopupFlags popup_flags = 0); // call to mark popup as open (don't call every frame!).
709  IMGUI_API void OpenPopup(ImGuiID id, ImGuiPopupFlags popup_flags = 0); // id overload to facilitate calling from nested stacks
710  IMGUI_API void OpenPopupOnItemClick(const char *str_id = NULL, ImGuiPopupFlags popup_flags = 1); // helper to open popup when clicked on last item. Default to ImGuiPopupFlags_MouseButtonRight == 1. (note: actually triggers on the mouse _released_ event to be consistent with popup behaviors)
711  IMGUI_API void CloseCurrentPopup(); // manually close the popup we have begin-ed into.
712 
713  // Popups: open+begin combined functions helpers
714  // - Helpers to do OpenPopup+BeginPopup where the Open action is triggered by e.g. hovering an item and right-clicking.
715  // - They are convenient to easily create context menus, hence the name.
716  // - IMPORTANT: Notice that BeginPopupContextXXX takes ImGuiPopupFlags just like OpenPopup() and unlike BeginPopup(). For full consistency, we may add ImGuiWindowFlags to the BeginPopupContextXXX functions in the future.
717  // - IMPORTANT: we exceptionally default their flags to 1 (== ImGuiPopupFlags_MouseButtonRight) for backward compatibility with older API taking 'int mouse_button = 1' parameter, so if you add other flags remember to re-add the ImGuiPopupFlags_MouseButtonRight.
718  IMGUI_API bool BeginPopupContextItem(const char *str_id = NULL, ImGuiPopupFlags popup_flags = 1); // open+begin popup when clicked on last item. Use str_id==NULL to associate the popup to previous item. If you want to use that on a non-interactive item such as Text() you need to pass in an explicit ID here. read comments in .cpp!
719  IMGUI_API bool BeginPopupContextWindow(const char *str_id = NULL, ImGuiPopupFlags popup_flags = 1);// open+begin popup when clicked on current window.
720  IMGUI_API bool BeginPopupContextVoid(const char *str_id = NULL, ImGuiPopupFlags popup_flags = 1); // open+begin popup when clicked in void (where there are no windows).
721 
722  // Popups: query functions
723  // - IsPopupOpen(): return true if the popup is open at the current BeginPopup() level of the popup stack.
724  // - IsPopupOpen() with ImGuiPopupFlags_AnyPopupId: return true if any popup is open at the current BeginPopup() level of the popup stack.
725  // - IsPopupOpen() with ImGuiPopupFlags_AnyPopupId + ImGuiPopupFlags_AnyPopupLevel: return true if any popup is open.
726  IMGUI_API bool IsPopupOpen(const char *str_id, ImGuiPopupFlags flags = 0); // return true if the popup is open.

728  // Tables
729  // [BETA API] API may evolve slightly! If you use this, please update to the next version when it comes out!
730  // - Full-featured replacement for old Columns API.
731  // - See Demo->Tables for demo code.
732  // - See top of imgui_tables.cpp for general commentary.
733  // - See ImGuiTableFlags_ and ImGuiTableColumnFlags_ enums for a description of available flags.
734  // The typical call flow is:
735  // - 1. Call BeginTable().
736  // - 2. Optionally call TableSetupColumn() to submit column name/flags/defaults.
737  // - 3. Optionally call TableSetupScrollFreeze() to request scroll freezing of columns/rows.
738  // - 4. Optionally call TableHeadersRow() to submit a header row. Names are pulled from TableSetupColumn() data.
739  // - 5. Populate contents:
740  // - In most situations you can use TableNextRow() + TableSetColumnIndex(N) to start appending into a column.
741  // - If you are using tables as a sort of grid, where every columns is holding the same type of contents,
742  // you may prefer using TableNextColumn() instead of TableNextRow() + TableSetColumnIndex().
743  // TableNextColumn() will automatically wrap-around into the next row if needed.
744  // - IMPORTANT: Comparatively to the old Columns() API, we need to call TableNextColumn() for the first column!
745  // - Summary of possible call flow:
746  // --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
747  // TableNextRow() -> TableSetColumnIndex(0) -> Text("Hello 0") -> TableSetColumnIndex(1) -> Text("Hello 1") // OK
748  // TableNextRow() -> TableNextColumn() -> Text("Hello 0") -> TableNextColumn() -> Text("Hello 1") // OK
749  // TableNextColumn() -> Text("Hello 0") -> TableNextColumn() -> Text("Hello 1") // OK: TableNextColumn() automatically gets to next row!
750  // TableNextRow() -> Text("Hello 0") // Not OK! Missing TableSetColumnIndex() or TableNextColumn()! Text will not appear!
751  // --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
752  // - 5. Call EndTable()
753  IMGUI_API bool BeginTable(const char *str_id, int column, ImGuiTableFlags flags = 0, const ImVec2 &outer_size = ImVec2(0.0f, 0.0f), float inner_width = 0.0f);
754  IMGUI_API void EndTable(); // only call EndTable() if BeginTable() returns true!
755  IMGUI_API void TableNextRow(ImGuiTableRowFlags row_flags = 0, float min_row_height = 0.0f); // append into the first cell of a new row.
756  IMGUI_API bool TableNextColumn(); // append into the next column (or first column of next row if currently in last column). Return true when column is visible.
757  IMGUI_API bool TableSetColumnIndex(int column_n); // append into the specified column. Return true when column is visible.
758 
759  // Tables: Headers & Columns declaration
760  // - Use TableSetupColumn() to specify label, resizing policy, default width/weight, id, various other flags etc.
761  // - Use TableHeadersRow() to create a header row and automatically submit a TableHeader() for each column.
762  // Headers are required to perform: reordering, sorting, and opening the context menu.
763  // The context menu can also be made available in columns body using ImGuiTableFlags_ContextMenuInBody.
764  // - You may manually submit headers using TableNextRow() + TableHeader() calls, but this is only useful in
765  // some advanced use cases (e.g. adding custom widgets in header row).
766  // - Use TableSetupScrollFreeze() to lock columns/rows so they stay visible when scrolled.
767  IMGUI_API void TableSetupColumn(const char *label, ImGuiTableColumnFlags flags = 0, float init_width_or_weight = 0.0f, ImGuiID user_id = 0);
768  IMGUI_API void TableSetupScrollFreeze(int cols, int rows); // lock columns/rows so they stay visible when scrolled.
769  IMGUI_API void TableHeadersRow(); // submit all headers cells based on data provided to TableSetupColumn() + submit context menu
770  IMGUI_API void TableHeader(const char *label); // submit one header cell manually (rarely used)
771 
772  // Tables: Sorting
773  // - Call TableGetSortSpecs() to retrieve latest sort specs for the table. NULL when not sorting.
774  // - When 'SpecsDirty == true' you should sort your data. It will be true when sorting specs have changed
775  // since last call, or the first time. Make sure to set 'SpecsDirty = false' after sorting, else you may
776  // wastefully sort your data every frame!
777  // - Lifetime: don't hold on this pointer over multiple frames or past any subsequent call to BeginTable().
778  IMGUI_API ImGuiTableSortSpecs *TableGetSortSpecs(); // get latest sort specs for the table (NULL if not sorting).
779

783  IMGUI_API int TableGetColumnIndex(); // return current column index.
784  IMGUI_API int TableGetRowIndex(); // return current row index.
785  IMGUI_API const char *TableGetColumnName(int column_n = -1); // return "" if column didn't have a name declared by TableSetupColumn(). Pass -1 to use current column.
786  IMGUI_API ImGuiTableColumnFlags TableGetColumnFlags(int column_n = -1); // return column flags so you can query their Enabled/Visible/Sorted/Hovered status flags. Pass -1 to use current column.
787  IMGUI_API void TableSetColumnEnabled(int column_n, bool v);// change user accessible enabled/disabled state of a column. Set to false to hide the column. User can use the context menu to change this themselves (right-click in headers, or right-click in columns body with ImGuiTableFlags_ContextMenuInBody)
788  IMGUI_API void TableSetBgColor(ImGuiTableBgTarget target, ImU32 color, int column_n = -1); // change the color of a cell, row, or column. See ImGuiTableBgTarget_ flags for details.

819  // Drag and Drop
820  // - On source items, call BeginDragDropSource(), if it returns true also call SetDragDropPayload() + EndDragDropSource().
821  // - On target candidates, call BeginDragDropTarget(), if it returns true also call AcceptDragDropPayload() + EndDragDropTarget().
822  // - If you stop calling BeginDragDropSource() the payload is preserved however it won't have a preview tooltip (we currently display a fallback "..." tooltip, see #1725)
823  // - An item can be both drag source and drop target.
824  IMGUI_API bool BeginDragDropSource(ImGuiDragDropFlags flags = 0); // call after submitting an item which may be dragged. when this return true, you can call SetDragDropPayload() + EndDragDropSource()
825  IMGUI_API bool SetDragDropPayload(const char *type, const void *data, size_t sz, ImGuiCond cond = 0); // type is a user defined string of maximum 32 characters. Strings starting with '_' are reserved for dear imgui internal types. Data is copied and held by imgui.
826  IMGUI_API void EndDragDropSource(); // only call EndDragDropSource() if BeginDragDropSource() returns true!
827  IMGUI_API bool BeginDragDropTarget(); // call after submitting an item that may receive a payload. If this returns true, you can call AcceptDragDropPayload() + EndDragDropTarget()
828  IMGUI_API const ImGuiPayload *AcceptDragDropPayload(const char *type, ImGuiDragDropFlags flags = 0); // accept contents of a given type. If ImGuiDragDropFlags_AcceptBeforeDelivery is set you can peek into the payload before the mouse button is released.
829  IMGUI_API void EndDragDropTarget(); // only call EndDragDropTarget() if BeginDragDropTarget() returns true!
830  IMGUI_API const ImGuiPayload *GetDragDropPayload(); // peek directly into the current payload from anywhere. may return NULL. use ImGuiPayload::IsDataType() to test for the payload type.

964 {
965  ImGuiWindowFlags_None = 0,
966  ImGuiWindowFlags_NoTitleBar = 1 << 0, // Disable title-bar
967  ImGuiWindowFlags_NoResize = 1 << 1, // Disable user resizing with the lower-right grip
968  ImGuiWindowFlags_NoMove = 1 << 2, // Disable user moving the window
969  ImGuiWindowFlags_NoScrollbar = 1 << 3, // Disable scrollbars (window can still scroll with mouse or programmatically)
970  ImGuiWindowFlags_NoScrollWithMouse = 1 << 4, // Disable user vertically scrolling with mouse wheel. On child window, mouse wheel will be forwarded to the parent unless NoScrollbar is also set.
971  ImGuiWindowFlags_NoCollapse = 1 << 5, // Disable user collapsing window by double-clicking on it
972  ImGuiWindowFlags_AlwaysAutoResize = 1 << 6, // Resize every window to its content every frame
973  ImGuiWindowFlags_NoBackground = 1 << 7, // Disable drawing background color (WindowBg, etc.) and outside border. Similar as using SetNextWindowBgAlpha(0.0f).
974  ImGuiWindowFlags_NoSavedSettings = 1 << 8, // Never load/save settings in .ini file
975  ImGuiWindowFlags_NoMouseInputs = 1 << 9, // Disable catching mouse, hovering test with pass through.
976  ImGuiWindowFlags_MenuBar = 1 << 10, // Has a menu-bar
977  ImGuiWindowFlags_HorizontalScrollbar = 1 << 11, // Allow horizontal scrollbar to appear (off by default). You may use SetNextWindowContentSize(ImVec2(width,0.0f)); prior to calling Begin() to specify width. Read code in imgui_demo in the "Horizontal Scrolling" section.
978  ImGuiWindowFlags_NoFocusOnAppearing = 1 << 12, // Disable taking focus when transitioning from hidden to visible state
979  ImGuiWindowFlags_NoBringToFrontOnFocus = 1 << 13, // Disable bringing window to front when taking focus (e.g. clicking on it or programmatically giving it focus)
980  ImGuiWindowFlags_AlwaysVerticalScrollbar = 1 << 14, // Always show vertical scrollbar (even if ContentSize.y < Size.y)
981  ImGuiWindowFlags_AlwaysHorizontalScrollbar = 1 << 15, // Always show horizontal scrollbar (even if ContentSize.x < Size.x)
982  ImGuiWindowFlags_AlwaysUseWindowPadding = 1 << 16, // Ensure child windows without border uses style.WindowPadding (ignored by default for non-bordered child windows, because more convenient)
983  ImGuiWindowFlags_NoNavInputs = 1 << 18, // No gamepad/keyboard navigation within the window
984  ImGuiWindowFlags_NoNavFocus = 1 << 19, // No focusing toward this window with gamepad/keyboard navigation (e.g. skipped by CTRL+TAB)
985  ImGuiWindowFlags_UnsavedDocument = 1 << 20, // Display a dot next to the title. When used in a tab/docking context, tab is selected when clicking the X + closure is not assumed (will wait for user to stop submitting the tab). Otherwise closure is assumed when pressing the X, so if you keep submitting the tab may reappear at end of tab bar.
986  ImGuiWindowFlags_NoNav = ImGuiWindowFlags_NoNavInputs | ImGuiWindowFlags_NoNavFocus,
987  ImGuiWindowFlags_NoDecoration = ImGuiWindowFlags_NoTitleBar | ImGuiWindowFlags_NoResize | ImGuiWindowFlags_NoScrollbar | ImGuiWindowFlags_NoCollapse,
988  ImGuiWindowFlags_NoInputs = ImGuiWindowFlags_NoMouseInputs | ImGuiWindowFlags_NoNavInputs | ImGuiWindowFlags_NoNavFocus,
989 
990  // [Internal]
991  ImGuiWindowFlags_NavFlattened = 1 << 23, // [BETA] Allow gamepad/keyboard navigation to cross over parent border to this child (only use on child that have no scrolling!)
992  ImGuiWindowFlags_ChildWindow = 1 << 24, // Don't use! For internal use by BeginChild()
993  ImGuiWindowFlags_Tooltip = 1 << 25, // Don't use! For internal use by BeginTooltip()
994  ImGuiWindowFlags_Popup = 1 << 26, // Don't use! For internal use by BeginPopup()
995  ImGuiWindowFlags_Modal = 1 << 27, // Don't use! For internal use by BeginPopupModal()
996  ImGuiWindowFlags_ChildMenu = 1 << 28 // Don't use! For internal use by BeginMenu()
997

1021  ImGuiInputTextFlags_Password = 1 << 15, // Password mode, display all characters as '*'
1022  ImGuiInputTextFlags_NoUndoRedo = 1 << 16, // Disable undo/redo. Note that input text owns the text data while active, if you want to provide your own undo/redo stack you need e.g. to call ClearActiveID().
1023  ImGuiInputTextFlags_CharsScientific = 1 << 17, // Allow 0123456789.+-*/eE (Scientific notation input)
1024  ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackResize = 1 << 18, // Callback on buffer capacity changes request (beyond 'buf_size' parameter value), allowing the string to grow. Notify when the string wants to be resized (for string types which hold a cache of their Size). You will be provided a new BufSize in the callback and NEED to honor it. (see misc/cpp/imgui_stdlib.h for an example of using this)
1025  ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackEdit = 1 << 19 // Callback on any edit (note that InputText() already returns true on edit, the callback is useful mainly to manipulate the underlying buffer while focus is active)

1055 // Flags for OpenPopup*(), BeginPopupContext*(), IsPopupOpen() functions.
1056 // - To be backward compatible with older API which took an 'int mouse_button = 1' argument, we need to treat
1057 // small flags values as a mouse button index, so we encode the mouse button in the first few bits of the flags.
1058 // It is therefore guaranteed to be legal to pass a mouse button index in ImGuiPopupFlags.
1059 // - For the same reason, we exceptionally default the ImGuiPopupFlags argument of BeginPopupContextXXX functions to 1 instead of 0.
1060 // IMPORTANT: because the default parameter is 1 (==ImGuiPopupFlags_MouseButtonRight), if you rely on the default parameter
1061 // and want to another another flag, you need to pass in the ImGuiPopupFlags_MouseButtonRight flag.
1062 // - Multiple buttons currently cannot be combined/or-ed in those functions (we could allow it later).
1063 enum ImGuiPopupFlags_
1064 {
1065  ImGuiPopupFlags_None = 0,
1066  ImGuiPopupFlags_MouseButtonLeft = 0, // For BeginPopupContext*(): open on Left Mouse release. Guaranteed to always be == 0 (same as ImGuiMouseButton_Left)
1067  ImGuiPopupFlags_MouseButtonRight = 1, // For BeginPopupContext*(): open on Right Mouse release. Guaranteed to always be == 1 (same as ImGuiMouseButton_Right)

1133 // Flags for ImGui::BeginTable()
1134 // [BETA API] API may evolve slightly! If you use this, please update to the next version when it comes out!
1135 // - Important! Sizing policies have complex and subtle side effects, more so than you would expect.
1136 // Read comments/demos carefully + experiment with live demos to get acquainted with them.
1137 // - The DEFAULT sizing policies are:
1138 // - Default to ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedFit if ScrollX is on, or if host window has ImGuiWindowFlags_AlwaysAutoResize.
1139 // - Default to ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchSame if ScrollX is off.
1140 // - When ScrollX is off:
1141 // - Table defaults to ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchSame -> all Columns defaults to ImGuiTableColumnFlags_WidthStretch with same weight.
1142 // - Columns sizing policy allowed: Stretch (default), Fixed/Auto.
1143 // - Fixed Columns will generally obtain their requested width (unless the table cannot fit them all).
1144 // - Stretch Columns will share the remaining width.
1145 // - Mixed Fixed/Stretch columns is possible but has various side-effects on resizing behaviors.
1146 // The typical use of mixing sizing policies is: any number of LEADING Fixed columns, followed by one or two TRAILING Stretch columns.
1147 // (this is because the visible order of columns have subtle but necessary effects on how they react to manual resizing).
1148 // - When ScrollX is on:
1149 // - Table defaults to ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedFit -> all Columns defaults to ImGuiTableColumnFlags_WidthFixed
1150 // - Columns sizing policy allowed: Fixed/Auto mostly.
1151 // - Fixed Columns can be enlarged as needed. Table will show an horizontal scrollbar if needed.
1152 // - When using auto-resizing (non-resizable) fixed columns, querying the content width to use item right-alignment e.g. SetNextItemWidth(-FLT_MIN) doesn't make sense, would create a feedback loop.
1153 // - Using Stretch columns OFTEN DOES NOT MAKE SENSE if ScrollX is on, UNLESS you have specified a value for 'inner_width' in BeginTable().
1154 // If you specify a value for 'inner_width' then effectively the scrolling space is known and Stretch or mixed Fixed/Stretch columns become meaningful again.
1155 // - Read on documentation at the top of imgui_tables.cpp for details.
1156 enum ImGuiTableFlags_
1157 {
1158  // Features
1159  ImGuiTableFlags_None = 0,
1160  ImGuiTableFlags_Resizable = 1 << 0, // Enable resizing columns.
1161  ImGuiTableFlags_Reorderable = 1 << 1, // Enable reordering columns in header row (need calling TableSetupColumn() + TableHeadersRow() to display headers)
1162  ImGuiTableFlags_Hideable = 1 << 2, // Enable hiding/disabling columns in context menu.
1163  ImGuiTableFlags_Sortable = 1 << 3, // Enable sorting. Call TableGetSortSpecs() to obtain sort specs. Also see ImGuiTableFlags_SortMulti and ImGuiTableFlags_SortTristate.
1164  ImGuiTableFlags_NoSavedSettings = 1 << 4, // Disable persisting columns order, width and sort settings in the .ini file.
1165  ImGuiTableFlags_ContextMenuInBody = 1 << 5, // Right-click on columns body/contents will display table context menu. By default it is available in TableHeadersRow().
1166  // Decorations
1167  ImGuiTableFlags_RowBg = 1 << 6, // Set each RowBg color with ImGuiCol_TableRowBg or ImGuiCol_TableRowBgAlt (equivalent of calling TableSetBgColor with ImGuiTableBgFlags_RowBg0 on each row manually)
1168  ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInnerH = 1 << 7, // Draw horizontal borders between rows.
1169  ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuterH = 1 << 8, // Draw horizontal borders at the top and bottom.
1170  ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInnerV = 1 << 9, // Draw vertical borders between columns.
1171  ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuterV = 1 << 10, // Draw vertical borders on the left and right sides.
1172  ImGuiTableFlags_BordersH = ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInnerH | ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuterH, // Draw horizontal borders.
1173  ImGuiTableFlags_BordersV = ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInnerV | ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuterV, // Draw vertical borders.
1174  ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInner = ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInnerV | ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInnerH, // Draw inner borders.
1175  ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuter = ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuterV | ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuterH, // Draw outer borders.
1176  ImGuiTableFlags_Borders = ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInner | ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuter, // Draw all borders.
1177  ImGuiTableFlags_NoBordersInBody = 1 << 11, // [ALPHA] Disable vertical borders in columns Body (borders will always appears in Headers). -> May move to style
1178  ImGuiTableFlags_NoBordersInBodyUntilResize = 1 << 12, // [ALPHA] Disable vertical borders in columns Body until hovered for resize (borders will always appears in Headers). -> May move to style
1179  // Sizing Policy (read above for defaults)
1180  ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedFit = 1 << 13, // Columns default to _WidthFixed or _WidthAuto (if resizable or not resizable), matching contents width.
1181  ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedSame = 2 << 13, // Columns default to _WidthFixed or _WidthAuto (if resizable or not resizable), matching the maximum contents width of all columns. Implicitly enable ImGuiTableFlags_NoKeepColumnsVisible.
1182  ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchProp = 3 << 13, // Columns default to _WidthStretch with default weights proportional to each columns contents widths.
1183  ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchSame = 4 << 13, // Columns default to _WidthStretch with default weights all equal, unless overridden by TableSetupColumn().
1184  // Sizing Extra Options
1185  ImGuiTableFlags_NoHostExtendX = 1 << 16, // Make outer width auto-fit to columns, overriding outer_size.x value. Only available when ScrollX/ScrollY are disabled and Stretch columns are not used.
1186  ImGuiTableFlags_NoHostExtendY = 1 << 17, // Make outer height stop exactly at outer_size.y (prevent auto-extending table past the limit). Only available when ScrollX/ScrollY are disabled. Data below the limit will be clipped and not visible.
1187  ImGuiTableFlags_NoKeepColumnsVisible = 1 << 18, // Disable keeping column always minimally visible when ScrollX is off and table gets too small. Not recommended if columns are resizable.
1188  ImGuiTableFlags_PreciseWidths = 1 << 19, // Disable distributing remainder width to stretched columns (width allocation on a 100-wide table with 3 columns: Without this flag: 33,33,34. With this flag: 33,33,33). With larger number of columns, resizing will appear to be less smooth.
1189  // Clipping
1190  ImGuiTableFlags_NoClip = 1 << 20, // Disable clipping rectangle for every individual columns (reduce draw command count, items will be able to overflow into other columns). Generally incompatible with TableSetupScrollFreeze().
1191  // Padding
1192  ImGuiTableFlags_PadOuterX = 1 << 21, // Default if BordersOuterV is on. Enable outer-most padding. Generally desirable if you have headers.
1193  ImGuiTableFlags_NoPadOuterX = 1 << 22, // Default if BordersOuterV is off. Disable outer-most padding.
1194  ImGuiTableFlags_NoPadInnerX = 1 << 23, // Disable inner padding between columns (double inner padding if BordersOuterV is on, single inner padding if BordersOuterV is off).
1195  // Scrolling
1196  ImGuiTableFlags_ScrollX = 1 << 24, // Enable horizontal scrolling. Require 'outer_size' parameter of BeginTable() to specify the container size. Changes default sizing policy. Because this create a child window, ScrollY is currently generally recommended when using ScrollX.
1197  ImGuiTableFlags_ScrollY = 1 << 25, // Enable vertical scrolling. Require 'outer_size' parameter of BeginTable() to specify the container size.
1198  // Sorting
1199  ImGuiTableFlags_SortMulti = 1 << 26, // Hold shift when clicking headers to sort on multiple column. TableGetSortSpecs() may return specs where (SpecsCount > 1).
1200  ImGuiTableFlags_SortTristate = 1 << 27, // Allow no sorting, disable default sorting. TableGetSortSpecs() may return specs where (SpecsCount == 0).
1201 
1202  // [Internal] Combinations and masks
1203  ImGuiTableFlags_SizingMask_ = ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedFit | ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedSame | ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchProp | ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchSame
1204 
1205  // Obsolete names (will be removed soon)
1206 #ifndef IMGUI_DISABLE_OBSOLETE_FUNCTIONS
1207  //, ImGuiTableFlags_ColumnsWidthFixed = ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedFit, ImGuiTableFlags_ColumnsWidthStretch = ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchSame // WIP Tables 2020/12
1208  //, ImGuiTableFlags_SizingPolicyFixed = ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedFit, ImGuiTableFlags_SizingPolicyStretch = ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchSame // WIP Tables 2021/01
1209 #endif
1210 };

1261 // Enum for ImGui::TableSetBgColor()
1262 // Background colors are rendering in 3 layers:
1263 // - Layer 0: draw with RowBg0 color if set, otherwise draw with ColumnBg0 if set.
1264 // - Layer 1: draw with RowBg1 color if set, otherwise draw with ColumnBg1 if set.
1265 // - Layer 2: draw with CellBg color if set.
1266 // The purpose of the two row/columns layers is to let you decide if a background color changes should override or blend with the existing color.
1267 // When using ImGuiTableFlags_RowBg on the table, each row has the RowBg0 color automatically set for odd/even rows.
1268 // If you set the color of RowBg0 target, your color will override the existing RowBg0 color.
1269 // If you set the color of RowBg1 or ColumnBg1 target, your color will blend over the RowBg0 color.
1270 enum ImGuiTableBgTarget_
1271 {
1272  ImGuiTableBgTarget_None = 0,
1273  ImGuiTableBgTarget_RowBg0 = 1, // Set row background color 0 (generally used for background, automatically set when ImGuiTableFlags_RowBg is used)
1274  ImGuiTableBgTarget_RowBg1 = 2, // Set row background color 1 (generally used for selection marking)
1275  ImGuiTableBgTarget_CellBg = 3 // Set cell background color (top-most color)
1276 };
1277

1283  ImGuiFocusedFlags_RootWindow = 1 << 1, // IsWindowFocused(): Test from root window (top most parent of the current hierarchy)
1284  ImGuiFocusedFlags_AnyWindow = 1 << 2, // IsWindowFocused(): Return true if any window is focused. Important: If you are trying to tell how to dispatch your low-level inputs, do NOT use this. Use 'io.WantCaptureMouse' instead! Please read the FAQ!
1285  ImGuiFocusedFlags_RootAndChildWindows = ImGuiFocusedFlags_RootWindow | ImGuiFocusedFlags_ChildWindows
1286 };

1435 // Configuration flags stored in io.ConfigFlags. Set by user/application.
1436 enum ImGuiConfigFlags_
1437 {
1438  ImGuiConfigFlags_None = 0,
1439  ImGuiConfigFlags_NavEnableKeyboard = 1 << 0, // Master keyboard navigation enable flag. NewFrame() will automatically fill io.NavInputs[] based on io.KeysDown[].
1440  ImGuiConfigFlags_NavEnableGamepad = 1 << 1, // Master gamepad navigation enable flag. This is mostly to instruct your imgui backend to fill io.NavInputs[]. Backend also needs to set ImGuiBackendFlags_HasGamepad.
1441  ImGuiConfigFlags_NavEnableSetMousePos = 1 << 2, // Instruct navigation to move the mouse cursor. May be useful on TV/console systems where moving a virtual mouse is awkward. Will update io.MousePos and set io.WantSetMousePos=true. If enabled you MUST honor io.WantSetMousePos requests in your backend, otherwise ImGui will react as if the mouse is jumping around back and forth.
1442  ImGuiConfigFlags_NavNoCaptureKeyboard = 1 << 3, // Instruct navigation to not set the io.WantCaptureKeyboard flag when io.NavActive is set.
1443  ImGuiConfigFlags_NoMouse = 1 << 4, // Instruct imgui to clear mouse position/buttons in NewFrame(). This allows ignoring the mouse information set by the backend.
1444  ImGuiConfigFlags_NoMouseCursorChange = 1 << 5, // Instruct backend to not alter mouse cursor shape and visibility. Use if the backend cursor changes are interfering with yours and you don't want to use SetMouseCursor() to change mouse cursor. You may want to honor requests from imgui by reading GetMouseCursor() yourself instead.
1445 
1446  // User storage (to allow your backend/engine to communicate to code that may be shared between multiple projects. Those flags are not used by core Dear ImGui)
1447  ImGuiConfigFlags_IsSRGB = 1 << 20, // Application is SRGB-aware.
1448  ImGuiConfigFlags_IsTouchScreen = 1 << 21 // Application is using a touch screen instead of a mouse.

1661 // Enumeration for ImGui::SetWindow***(), SetNextWindow***(), SetNextItem***() functions

1673 //-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1674 // [SECTION] Helpers: Memory allocations macros, ImVector<>
1675 //-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1676 
1677 //-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1678 // IM_MALLOC(), IM_FREE(), IM_NEW(), IM_PLACEMENT_NEW(), IM_DELETE()
1679 // We call C++ constructor on own allocated memory via the placement "new(ptr) Type()" syntax.
1680 // Defining a custom placement new() with a custom parameter allows us to bypass including <new> which on some platforms complains when user has disabled exceptions.
1681 //-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1682 
1683 struct ImNewWrapper
1684 {};
1685 inline void *operator new(size_t, ImNewWrapper, void *ptr)
1686 {
1687  return ptr;
1688 }
1689 inline void operator delete(void *, ImNewWrapper, void *)
1690 {} // This is only required so we can use the symmetrical new()
1691 #define IM_ALLOC(_SIZE) ImGui::MemAlloc(_SIZE)
1692 #define IM_FREE(_PTR) ImGui::MemFree(_PTR)
1693 #define IM_PLACEMENT_NEW(_PTR) new(ImNewWrapper(), _PTR)
1694 #define IM_NEW(_TYPE) new(ImNewWrapper(), ImGui::MemAlloc(sizeof(_TYPE))) _TYPE
1695 template<typename T> void IM_DELETE(T *p)
1696 {
1697  if (p)
1698  {
1699  p->~T(); ImGui::MemFree(p);
1700  }
1701 }
1702 
1703 //-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1704 // ImVector<>
1705 // Lightweight std::vector<>-like class to avoid dragging dependencies (also, some implementations of STL with debug enabled are absurdly slow, we bypass it so our code runs fast in debug).
1706 //-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1707 // - You generally do NOT need to care or use this ever. But we need to make it available in imgui.h because some of our public structures are relying on it.
1708 // - We use std-like naming convention here, which is a little unusual for this codebase.
1709 // - Important: clear() frees memory, resize(0) keep the allocated buffer. We use resize(0) a lot to intentionally recycle allocated buffers across frames and amortize our costs.
1710 // - Important: our implementation does NOT call C++ constructors/destructors, we treat everything as raw data! This is intentional but be extra mindful of that,
1711 // Do NOT use this class as a std::vector replacement in your own code! Many of the structures used by dear imgui can be safely initialized by a zero-memset.
1712 //-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1713 
1714 IM_MSVC_RUNTIME_CHECKS_OFF
1715 template<typename T>
1716 struct ImVector
1717 {
1718  int Size;
1719  int Capacity;
1720  T *Data;
1721 
1722  // Provide standard typedefs but we don't use them ourselves.
1723  typedef T value_type;
1724  typedef value_type *iterator;
1725  typedef const value_type *const_iterator;
1726 
1727  // Constructors, destructor
1728  inline ImVector()
1729  {
1730  Size = Capacity = 0; Data = NULL;
1731  }
1732  inline ImVector(const ImVector<T> &src)
1733  {
1734  Size = Capacity = 0; Data = NULL; operator=(src);
1735  }
1736  inline ImVector<T> &operator=(const ImVector<T> &src)
1737  {
1738  clear(); resize(src.Size); memcpy(Data, src.Data, (size_t)Size * sizeof(T)); return *this;
1739  }
1740  inline ~ImVector()
1741  {
1742  if (Data) IM_FREE(Data);
1743  } // Important: does not destruct anything
1744 
1745  inline void clear()
1746  {
1747  if (Data)
1748  {
1749  Size = Capacity = 0; IM_FREE(Data); Data = NULL;
1750  }
1751  } // Important: does not destruct anything
1752  inline void clear_delete()
1753  {
1754  for (int n = 0; n < Size; n++) IM_DELETE(Data[n]); clear();
1755  } // Important: never called automatically! always explicit.
1756  inline void clear_destruct()
1757  {
1758  for (int n = 0; n < Size; n++) Data[n].~T(); clear();
1759  } // Important: never called automatically! always explicit.
1760 
1761  inline bool empty() const
1762  {
1763  return Size == 0;
1764  }
1765  inline int size() const
1766  {
1767  return Size;
1768  }
1769  inline int size_in_bytes() const
1770  {
1771  return Size * (int)sizeof(T);
1772  }
1773  inline int max_size() const
1774  {
1775  return 0x7FFFFFFF / (int)sizeof(T);
1776  }
1777  inline int capacity() const
1778  {
1779  return Capacity;
1780  }
1781  inline T &operator[](int i)
1782  {
1783  IM_ASSERT(i >= 0 && i < Size); return Data[i];
1784  }
1785  inline const T &operator[](int i) const
1786  {
1787  IM_ASSERT(i >= 0 && i < Size); return Data[i];
1788  }
1789 
1790  inline T *begin()
1791  {
1792  return Data;
1793  }
1794  inline const T *begin() const
1795  {
1796  return Data;
1797  }
1798  inline T *end()
1799  {
1800  return Data + Size;
1801  }
1802  inline const T *end() const
1803  {
1804  return Data + Size;
1805  }
1806  inline T &front()
1807  {
1808  IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[0];
1809  }
1810  inline const T &front() const
1811  {
1812  IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[0];
1813  }
1814  inline T &back()
1815  {
1816  IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[Size - 1];
1817  }
1818  inline const T &back() const
1819  {
1820  IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[Size - 1];
1821  }
1822  inline void swap(ImVector<T> &rhs)
1823  {
1824  int rhs_size = rhs.Size; rhs.Size = Size; Size = rhs_size; int rhs_cap = rhs.Capacity; rhs.Capacity = Capacity; Capacity = rhs_cap; T *rhs_data = rhs.Data; rhs.Data = Data; Data = rhs_data;
1825  }
1826 
1827  inline int _grow_capacity(int sz) const
1828  {
1829  int new_capacity = Capacity ? (Capacity + Capacity / 2) : 8; return new_capacity > sz ? new_capacity : sz;
1830  }
1831  inline void resize(int new_size)
1832  {
1833  if (new_size > Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(new_size)); Size = new_size;
1834  }
1835  inline void resize(int new_size, const T &v)
1836  {
1837  if (new_size > Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(new_size)); if (new_size > Size) for (int n = Size; n < new_size; n++) memcpy(&Data[n], &v, sizeof(v)); Size = new_size;
1838  }
1839  inline void shrink(int new_size)
1840  {
1841  IM_ASSERT(new_size <= Size); Size = new_size;
1842  } // Resize a vector to a smaller size, guaranteed not to cause a reallocation
1843  inline void reserve(int new_capacity)
1844  {
1845  if (new_capacity <= Capacity) return; T *new_data = (T *)IM_ALLOC((size_t)new_capacity * sizeof(T)); if (Data)
1846  {
1847  memcpy(new_data, Data, (size_t)Size * sizeof(T)); IM_FREE(Data);
1848  } Data = new_data; Capacity = new_capacity;
1849  }
1850 
1851  // NB: It is illegal to call push_back/push_front/insert with a reference pointing inside the ImVector data itself! e.g. v.push_back(v[10]) is forbidden.
1852  inline void push_back(const T &v)
1853  {
1854  if (Size == Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(Size + 1)); memcpy(&Data[Size], &v, sizeof(v)); Size++;
1855  }
1856  inline void pop_back()
1857  {
1858  IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); Size--;
1859  }
1860  inline void push_front(const T &v)
1861  {
1862  if (Size == 0) push_back(v); else insert(Data, v);
1863  }
1864  inline T *erase(const T *it)
1865  {
1866  IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < Data + Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; memmove(Data + off, Data + off + 1, ((size_t)Size - (size_t)off - 1) * sizeof(T)); Size--; return Data + off;
1867  }
1868  inline T *erase(const T *it, const T *it_last)
1869  {
1870  IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < Data + Size && it_last > it && it_last <= Data + Size); const ptrdiff_t count = it_last - it; const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; memmove(Data + off, Data + off + count, ((size_t)Size - (size_t)off - count) * sizeof(T)); Size -= (int)count; return Data + off;
1871  }
1872  inline T *erase_unsorted(const T *it)
1873  {
1874  IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < Data + Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; if (it < Data + Size - 1) memcpy(Data + off, Data + Size - 1, sizeof(T)); Size--; return Data + off;
1875  }
1876  inline T *insert(const T *it, const T &v)
1877  {
1878  IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it <= Data + Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; if (Size == Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(Size + 1)); if (off < (int)Size) memmove(Data + off + 1, Data + off, ((size_t)Size - (size_t)off) * sizeof(T)); memcpy(&Data[off], &v, sizeof(v)); Size++; return Data + off;
1879  }
1880  inline bool contains(const T &v) const
1881  {
1882  const T *data = Data; const T *data_end = Data + Size; while (data < data_end) if (*data++ == v) return true; return false;
1883  }
1884  inline T *find(const T &v)
1885  {
1886  T *data = Data; const T *data_end = Data + Size; while (data < data_end) if (*data == v) break; else ++data; return data;
1887  }
1888  inline const T *find(const T &v) const
1889  {
1890  const T *data = Data; const T *data_end = Data + Size; while (data < data_end) if (*data == v) break; else ++data; return data;
1891  }
1892  inline bool find_erase(const T &v)
1893  {
1894  const T *it = find(v); if (it < Data + Size)
1895  {
1896  erase(it); return true;
1897  } return false;
1898  }
1899  inline bool find_erase_unsorted(const T &v)
1900  {
1901  const T *it = find(v); if (it < Data + Size)
1902  {
1903  erase_unsorted(it); return true;
1904  } return false;
1905  }
1906  inline int index_from_ptr(const T *it) const
1907  {
1908  IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < Data + Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; return (int)off;
1909  }
1910 };
1911 IM_MSVC_RUNTIME_CHECKS_RESTORE
1912 
1913 //-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1914 // [SECTION] ImGuiStyle
1915 //-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1916 // You may modify the ImGui::GetStyle() main instance during initialization and before NewFrame().
1917 // During the frame, use ImGui::PushStyleVar(ImGuiStyleVar_XXXX)/PopStyleVar() to alter the main style values,
1918 // and ImGui::PushStyleColor(ImGuiCol_XXX)/PopStyleColor() for colors.
1919 //-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1920 
1921 struct ImGuiStyle
1922 {
1923  float Alpha; // Global alpha applies to everything in Dear ImGui.
1924  float DisabledAlpha; // Additional alpha multiplier applied by BeginDisabled(). Multiply over current value of Alpha.
1925  ImVec2 WindowPadding; // Padding within a window.
1926  float WindowRounding; // Radius of window corners rounding. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular windows. Large values tend to lead to variety of artifacts and are not recommended.
1927  float WindowBorderSize; // Thickness of border around windows. Generally set to 0.0f or 1.0f. (Other values are not well tested and more CPU/GPU costly).
1928  ImVec2 WindowMinSize; // Minimum window size. This is a global setting. If you want to constraint individual windows, use SetNextWindowSizeConstraints().
1929  ImVec2 WindowTitleAlign; // Alignment for title bar text. Defaults to (0.0f,0.5f) for left-aligned,vertically centered.
1930  ImGuiDir WindowMenuButtonPosition; // Side of the collapsing/docking button in the title bar (None/Left/Right). Defaults to ImGuiDir_Left.
1931  float ChildRounding; // Radius of child window corners rounding. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular windows.
1932  float ChildBorderSize; // Thickness of border around child windows. Generally set to 0.0f or 1.0f. (Other values are not well tested and more CPU/GPU costly).
1933  float PopupRounding; // Radius of popup window corners rounding. (Note that tooltip windows use WindowRounding)
1934  float PopupBorderSize; // Thickness of border around popup/tooltip windows. Generally set to 0.0f or 1.0f. (Other values are not well tested and more CPU/GPU costly).
1935  ImVec2 FramePadding; // Padding within a framed rectangle (used by most widgets).
1936  float FrameRounding; // Radius of frame corners rounding. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular frame (used by most widgets).
1937  float FrameBorderSize; // Thickness of border around frames. Generally set to 0.0f or 1.0f. (Other values are not well tested and more CPU/GPU costly).
1938  ImVec2 ItemSpacing; // Horizontal and vertical spacing between widgets/lines.
1939  ImVec2 ItemInnerSpacing; // Horizontal and vertical spacing between within elements of a composed widget (e.g. a slider and its label).
1940  ImVec2 CellPadding; // Padding within a table cell
1941  ImVec2 TouchExtraPadding; // Expand reactive bounding box for touch-based system where touch position is not accurate enough. Unfortunately we don't sort widgets so priority on overlap will always be given to the first widget. So don't grow this too much!
1942  float IndentSpacing; // Horizontal indentation when e.g. entering a tree node. Generally == (FontSize + FramePadding.x*2).
1943  float ColumnsMinSpacing; // Minimum horizontal spacing between two columns. Preferably > (FramePadding.x + 1).
1944  float ScrollbarSize; // Width of the vertical scrollbar, Height of the horizontal scrollbar.
1945  float ScrollbarRounding; // Radius of grab corners for scrollbar.
1946  float GrabMinSize; // Minimum width/height of a grab box for slider/scrollbar.
1947  float GrabRounding; // Radius of grabs corners rounding. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular slider grabs.
1948  float LogSliderDeadzone; // The size in pixels of the dead-zone around zero on logarithmic sliders that cross zero.
1949  float TabRounding; // Radius of upper corners of a tab. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular tabs.
1950  float TabBorderSize; // Thickness of border around tabs.
1951  float TabMinWidthForCloseButton; // Minimum width for close button to appears on an unselected tab when hovered. Set to 0.0f to always show when hovering, set to FLT_MAX to never show close button unless selected.
1952  ImGuiDir ColorButtonPosition; // Side of the color button in the ColorEdit4 widget (left/right). Defaults to ImGuiDir_Right.
1953  ImVec2 ButtonTextAlign; // Alignment of button text when button is larger than text. Defaults to (0.5f, 0.5f) (centered).
1954  ImVec2 SelectableTextAlign; // Alignment of selectable text. Defaults to (0.0f, 0.0f) (top-left aligned). It's generally important to keep this left-aligned if you want to lay multiple items on a same line.
1955  ImVec2 DisplayWindowPadding; // Window position are clamped to be visible within the display area or monitors by at least this amount. Only applies to regular windows.
1956  ImVec2 DisplaySafeAreaPadding; // If you cannot see the edges of your screen (e.g. on a TV) increase the safe area padding. Apply to popups/tooltips as well regular windows. NB: Prefer configuring your TV sets correctly!
1957  float MouseCursorScale; // Scale software rendered mouse cursor (when io.MouseDrawCursor is enabled). May be removed later.
1958  bool AntiAliasedLines; // Enable anti-aliased lines/borders. Disable if you are really tight on CPU/GPU. Latched at the beginning of the frame (copied to ImDrawList).
1959  bool AntiAliasedLinesUseTex; // Enable anti-aliased lines/borders using textures where possible. Require backend to render with bilinear filtering. Latched at the beginning of the frame (copied to ImDrawList).
1960  bool AntiAliasedFill; // Enable anti-aliased edges around filled shapes (rounded rectangles, circles, etc.). Disable if you are really tight on CPU/GPU. Latched at the beginning of the frame (copied to ImDrawList).
1961  float CurveTessellationTol; // Tessellation tolerance when using PathBezierCurveTo() without a specific number of segments. Decrease for highly tessellated curves (higher quality, more polygons), increase to reduce quality.
1962  float CircleTessellationMaxError; // Maximum error (in pixels) allowed when using AddCircle()/AddCircleFilled() or drawing rounded corner rectangles with no explicit segment count specified. Decrease for higher quality but more geometry.
1963  ImVec4 Colors[ImGuiCol_COUNT];
1964 
1965  IMGUI_API ImGuiStyle();
1966  IMGUI_API void ScaleAllSizes(float scale_factor);
1967 };

2107 //-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2108 // [SECTION] Misc data structures
2109 //-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2110 
2111 // Shared state of InputText(), passed as an argument to your callback when a ImGuiInputTextFlags_Callback* flag is used.
2112 // The callback function should return 0 by default.
2113 // Callbacks (follow a flag name and see comments in ImGuiInputTextFlags_ declarations for more details)
2114 // - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackEdit: Callback on buffer edit (note that InputText() already returns true on edit, the callback is useful mainly to manipulate the underlying buffer while focus is active)
2115 // - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackAlways: Callback on each iteration
2116 // - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackCompletion: Callback on pressing TAB
2117 // - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackHistory: Callback on pressing Up/Down arrows
2118 // - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackCharFilter: Callback on character inputs to replace or discard them. Modify 'EventChar' to replace or discard, or return 1 in callback to discard.
2119 // - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackResize: Callback on buffer capacity changes request (beyond 'buf_size' parameter value), allowing the string to grow.
2120 struct ImGuiInputTextCallbackData
2121 {
2122  ImGuiInputTextFlags EventFlag; // One ImGuiInputTextFlags_Callback* // Read-only
2123  ImGuiInputTextFlags Flags; // What user passed to InputText() // Read-only
2124  void *UserData; // What user passed to InputText() // Read-only
2125 
2126  // Arguments for the different callback events
2127  // - To modify the text buffer in a callback, prefer using the InsertChars() / DeleteChars() function. InsertChars() will take care of calling the resize callback if necessary.
2128  // - If you know your edits are not going to resize the underlying buffer allocation, you may modify the contents of 'Buf[]' directly. You need to update 'BufTextLen' accordingly (0 <= BufTextLen < BufSize) and set 'BufDirty'' to true so InputText can update its internal state.
2129  ImWchar EventChar; // Character input // Read-write // [CharFilter] Replace character with another one, or set to zero to drop. return 1 is equivalent to setting EventChar=0;
2130  ImGuiKey EventKey; // Key pressed (Up/Down/TAB) // Read-only // [Completion,History]
2131  char *Buf; // Text buffer // Read-write // [Resize] Can replace pointer / [Completion,History,Always] Only write to pointed data, don't replace the actual pointer!
2132  int BufTextLen; // Text length (in bytes) // Read-write // [Resize,Completion,History,Always] Exclude zero-terminator storage. In C land: == strlen(some_text), in C++ land: string.length()
2133  int BufSize; // Buffer size (in bytes) = capacity+1 // Read-only // [Resize,Completion,History,Always] Include zero-terminator storage. In C land == ARRAYSIZE(my_char_array), in C++ land: string.capacity()+1
2134  bool BufDirty; // Set if you modify Buf/BufTextLen! // Write // [Completion,History,Always]
2135  int CursorPos; // // Read-write // [Completion,History,Always]
2136  int SelectionStart; // // Read-write // [Completion,History,Always] == to SelectionEnd when no selection)
2137  int SelectionEnd; // // Read-write // [Completion,History,Always]
2138 
2139  // Helper functions for text manipulation.
2140  // Use those function to benefit from the CallbackResize behaviors. Calling those function reset the selection.
2141  IMGUI_API ImGuiInputTextCallbackData();
2142  IMGUI_API void DeleteChars(int pos, int bytes_count);
2143  IMGUI_API void InsertChars(int pos, const char *text, const char *text_end = NULL);

2349 // Helper: Key->Value storage
2350 // Typically you don't have to worry about this since a storage is held within each Window.
2351 // We use it to e.g. store collapse state for a tree (Int 0/1)
2352 // This is optimized for efficient lookup (dichotomy into a contiguous buffer) and rare insertion (typically tied to user interactions aka max once a frame)
2353 // You can use it as custom user storage for temporary values. Declare your own storage if, for example:
2354 // - You want to manipulate the open/close state of a particular sub-tree in your interface (tree node uses Int 0/1 to store their state).
2355 // - You want to store custom debug data easily without adding or editing structures in your code (probably not efficient, but convenient)
2356 // Types are NOT stored, so it is up to you to make sure your Key don't collide with different types.
2357 struct ImGuiStorage
2358 {
2359  // [Internal]
2360  struct ImGuiStoragePair
2361  {
2362  ImGuiID key;
2363  union
2364  {
2365  int val_i; float val_f; void *val_p;
2366  };
2367  ImGuiStoragePair(ImGuiID _key, int _val_i)
2368  {
2369  key = _key; val_i = _val_i;
2370  }
2371  ImGuiStoragePair(ImGuiID _key, float _val_f)
2372  {
2373  key = _key; val_f = _val_f;
2374  }
2375  ImGuiStoragePair(ImGuiID _key, void *_val_p)
2376  {
2377  key = _key; val_p = _val_p;
2378  }
2379  };
2380 
2381  ImVector<ImGuiStoragePair> Data;
2382 
2383  // - Get***() functions find pair, never add/allocate. Pairs are sorted so a query is O(log N)
2384  // - Set***() functions find pair, insertion on demand if missing.
2385  // - Sorted insertion is costly, paid once. A typical frame shouldn't need to insert any new pair.
2386  void Clear()
2387  {
2388  Data.clear();
2389  }
2390  IMGUI_API int GetInt(ImGuiID key, int default_val = 0) const;
2391  IMGUI_API void SetIntUniform(ImGuiID key, int val);
2392  IMGUI_API bool GetBool(ImGuiID key, bool default_val = false) const;
2393  IMGUI_API void SetBoolUniform(ImGuiID key, bool val);
2394  IMGUI_API float GetFloat(ImGuiID key, float default_val = 0.0f) const;
2395  IMGUI_API void SetFloatUniform(ImGuiID key, float val);
2396  IMGUI_API void *GetVoidPtr(ImGuiID key) const; // default_val is NULL
2397  IMGUI_API void SetVoidPtr(ImGuiID key, void *val);
2398 
2399  // - Get***Ref() functions finds pair, insert on demand if missing, return pointer. Useful if you intend to do Get+Set.
2400  // - References are only valid until a new value is added to the storage. Calling a Set***() function or a Get***Ref() function invalidates the pointer.
2401  // - A typical use case where this is convenient for quick hacking (e.g. add storage during a live Edit&Continue session if you can't modify existing struct)
2402  // float* pvar = ImGui::GetFloatRef(key); ImGui::SliderFloat("var", pvar, 0, 100.0f); some_var += *pvar;
2403  IMGUI_API int *GetIntRef(ImGuiID key, int default_val = 0);
2404  IMGUI_API bool *GetBoolRef(ImGuiID key, bool default_val = false);
2405  IMGUI_API float *GetFloatRef(ImGuiID key, float default_val = 0.0f);
2406  IMGUI_API void **GetVoidPtrRef(ImGuiID key, void *default_val = NULL);
2407 
2408  // Use on your own storage if you know only integer are being stored (open/close all tree nodes)
2409  IMGUI_API void SetAllInt(int val);
2410 
2411  // For quicker full rebuild of a storage (instead of an incremental one), you may add all your contents and then sort once.
2412  IMGUI_API void BuildSortByKey();
2413 };

2415 // Helper: Manually clip large list of items.
2416 // If you are submitting lots of evenly spaced items and you have a random access to the list, you can perform coarse
2417 // clipping based on visibility to save yourself from processing those items at all.
2418 // The clipper calculates the range of visible items and advance the cursor to compensate for the non-visible items we have skipped.
2419 // (Dear ImGui already clip items based on their bounds but it needs to measure text size to do so, whereas manual coarse clipping before submission makes this cost and your own data fetching/submission cost almost null)
2420 // Usage:
2421 // ImGuiListClipper clipper;
2422 // clipper.Begin(1000); // We have 1000 elements, evenly spaced.
2423 // while (clipper.Step())
2424 // for (int i = clipper.DisplayStart; i < clipper.DisplayEnd; i++)
2425 // ImGui::Text("line number %d", i);
2426 // Generally what happens is:
2427 // - Clipper lets you process the first element (DisplayStart = 0, DisplayEnd = 1) regardless of it being visible or not.
2428 // - User code submit one element.
2429 // - Clipper can measure the height of the first element
2430 // - Clipper calculate the actual range of elements to display based on the current clipping rectangle, position the cursor before the first visible element.
2431 // - User code submit visible elements.
2432 struct ImGuiListClipper
2433 {
2434  int DisplayStart;
2435  int DisplayEnd;
2436 
2437  // [Internal]
2438  int ItemsCount;
2439  int StepNo;
2440  int ItemsFrozen;
2441  float ItemsHeight;
2442  float StartPosY;
2443 
2444  IMGUI_API ImGuiListClipper();
2445  IMGUI_API ~ImGuiListClipper();
2446 
2447  // items_count: Use INT_MAX if you don't know how many items you have (in which case the cursor won't be advanced in the final step)
2448  // items_height: Use -1.0f to be calculated automatically on first step. Otherwise pass in the distance between your items, typically GetTextLineHeightWithSpacing() or GetFrameHeightWithSpacing().
2449  IMGUI_API void Begin(int items_count, float items_height = -1.0f); // Automatically called by constructor if you passed 'items_count' or by Step() in Step 1.
2450  IMGUI_API void End(); // Automatically called on the last call of Step() that returns false.
2451  IMGUI_API bool Step(); // Call until it returns false. The DisplayStart/DisplayEnd fields will be set and you can process/draw those items.
2452 
2453 #ifndef IMGUI_DISABLE_OBSOLETE_FUNCTIONS
2454  inline ImGuiListClipper(int items_count, float items_height = -1.0f)
2455  {
2456  memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this)); ItemsCount = -1; Begin(items_count, items_height);
2457  } // [removed in 1.79]
2458 #endif
2459 };
