2461 // Helpers macros to generate 32-bit encoded colors
2462 #ifdef IMGUI_USE_BGRA_PACKED_COLOR
2463 #define IM_COL32_R_SHIFT 16
2464 #define IM_COL32_G_SHIFT 8
2465 #define IM_COL32_B_SHIFT 0
2466 #define IM_COL32_A_SHIFT 24
2467 #define IM_COL32_A_MASK 0xFF000000
2468 #else
2469 #define IM_COL32_R_SHIFT 0
2470 #define IM_COL32_G_SHIFT 8
2471 #define IM_COL32_B_SHIFT 16
2472 #define IM_COL32_A_SHIFT 24
2473 #define IM_COL32_A_MASK 0xFF000000
2474 #endif
2475 #define IM_COL32(R,G,B,A) (((ImU32)(A)<<IM_COL32_A_SHIFT) | ((ImU32)(B)<<IM_COL32_B_SHIFT) | ((ImU32)(G)<<IM_COL32_G_SHIFT) | ((ImU32)(R)<<IM_COL32_R_SHIFT))
2476 #define IM_COL32_WHITE IM_COL32(255,255,255,255) // Opaque white = 0xFFFFFFFF
2477 #define IM_COL32_BLACK IM_COL32(0,0,0,255) // Opaque black
2478 #define IM_COL32_BLACK_TRANS IM_COL32(0,0,0,0) // Transparent black = 0x00000000
2479 
2480 // Helper: ImColor() implicitly converts colors to either ImU32 (packed 4x1 byte) or ImVec4 (4x1 float)
2481 // Prefer using IM_COL32() macros if you want a guaranteed compile-time ImU32 for usage with ImDrawList API.
2482 // **Avoid storing ImColor! Store either u32 of ImVec4. This is not a full-featured color class. MAY OBSOLETE.
2483 // **None of the ImGui API are using ImColor directly but you can use it as a convenience to pass colors in either ImU32 or ImVec4 formats. Explicitly cast to ImU32 or ImVec4 if needed.
2484 struct ImColor
2485 {
2486  ImVec4 Value;
2487 
2488  ImColor()
2489  {
2490  Value.x = Value.y = Value.z = Value.w = 0.0f;
2491  }
2492  ImColor(int r, int g, int b, int a = 255)
2493  {
2494  float sc = 1.0f / 255.0f; Value.x = (float)r * sc; Value.y = (float)g * sc; Value.z = (float)b * sc; Value.w = (float)a * sc;
2495  }
2496  ImColor(ImU32 rgba)
2497  {
2498  float sc = 1.0f / 255.0f; Value.x = (float)((rgba >> IM_COL32_R_SHIFT) & 0xFF) * sc; Value.y = (float)((rgba >> IM_COL32_G_SHIFT) & 0xFF) * sc; Value.z = (float)((rgba >> IM_COL32_B_SHIFT) & 0xFF) * sc; Value.w = (float)((rgba >> IM_COL32_A_SHIFT) & 0xFF) * sc;
2499  }
2500  ImColor(float r, float g, float b, float a = 1.0f)
2501  {
2502  Value.x = r; Value.y = g; Value.z = b; Value.w = a;
2503  }
2504  ImColor(const ImVec4 &col)
2505  {
2506  Value = col;
2507  }
2508  inline operator ImU32() const
2509  {
2510  return ImGui::ColorConvertFloat4ToU32(Value);
2511  }
2512  inline operator ImVec4() const
2513  {
2514  return Value;
2515  }
2516 
2517  // FIXME-OBSOLETE: May need to obsolete/cleanup those helpers.
2518  inline void SetHSV(float h, float s, float v, float a = 1.0f)
2519  {
2520  ImGui::ColorConvertHSVtoRGB(h, s, v, Value.x, Value.y, Value.z); Value.w = a;
2521  }
2522  static ImColor HSV(float h, float s, float v, float a = 1.0f)
2523  {
2524  float r, g, b; ImGui::ColorConvertHSVtoRGB(h, s, v, r, g, b); return ImColor(r, g, b, a);
2525  }
2526 };

2528 //-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2529 // [SECTION] Drawing API (ImDrawCmd, ImDrawIdx, ImDrawVert, ImDrawChannel, ImDrawListSplitter, ImDrawListFlags, ImDrawList, ImDrawData)
2530 // Hold a series of drawing commands. The user provides a renderer for ImDrawData which essentially contains an array of ImDrawList.
2531 //-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2532 
2533 // The maximum line width to bake anti-aliased textures for. Build atlas with ImFontAtlasFlags_NoBakedLines to disable baking.
2534 #ifndef IM_DRAWLIST_TEX_LINES_WIDTH_MAX
2535 #define IM_DRAWLIST_TEX_LINES_WIDTH_MAX (63)
2536 #endif
2537 
2538 // ImDrawCallback: Draw callbacks for advanced uses [configurable type: override in imconfig.h]
2539 // NB: You most likely do NOT need to use draw callbacks just to create your own widget or customized UI rendering,
2540 // you can poke into the draw list for that! Draw callback may be useful for example to:
2541 // A) Change your GPU render state,
2542 // B) render a complex 3D scene inside a UI element without an intermediate texture/render target, etc.
2543 // The expected behavior from your rendering function is 'if (cmd.UserCallback != NULL) { cmd.UserCallback(parent_list, cmd); } else { RenderTriangles() }'
2544 // If you want to override the signature of ImDrawCallback, you can simply use e.g. '#define ImDrawCallback MyDrawCallback' (in imconfig.h) + update rendering backend accordingly.
2545 #ifndef ImDrawCallback
2546 typedef void (*ImDrawCallback)(const ImDrawList *parent_list, const ImDrawCmd *cmd);
2547 #endif
2548 
2549 // Special Draw callback value to request renderer backend to reset the graphics/render state.
2550 // The renderer backend needs to handle this special value, otherwise it will crash trying to call a function at this address.
2551 // This is useful for example if you submitted callbacks which you know have altered the render state and you want it to be restored.
2552 // It is not done by default because they are many perfectly useful way of altering render state for imgui contents (e.g. changing shader/blending settings before an Image call).
2553 #define ImDrawCallback_ResetRenderState (ImDrawCallback)(-1)
2554 
2555 // Typically, 1 command = 1 GPU draw call (unless command is a callback)
2556 // - VtxOffset/IdxOffset: When 'io.BackendFlags & ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasVtxOffset' is enabled,
2557 // those fields allow us to render meshes larger than 64K vertices while keeping 16-bit indices.
2558 // Pre-1.71 backends will typically ignore the VtxOffset/IdxOffset fields.
2559 // - The ClipRect/TextureId/VtxOffset fields must be contiguous as we memcmp() them together (this is asserted for).
2560 struct ImDrawCmd
2561 {
2562  ImVec4 ClipRect; // 4*4 // Clipping rectangle (x1, y1, x2, y2). Subtract ImDrawData->DisplayPos to get clipping rectangle in "viewport" coordinates
2563  ImTextureID TextureId; // 4-8 // User-provided texture ID. Set by user in ImfontAtlas::SetTexID() for fonts or passed to Image*() functions. Ignore if never using images or multiple fonts atlas.
2564  unsigned int VtxOffset; // 4 // Start offset in vertex buffer. ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasVtxOffset: always 0, otherwise may be >0 to support meshes larger than 64K vertices with 16-bit indices.
2565  unsigned int IdxOffset; // 4 // Start offset in index buffer. Always equal to sum of ElemCount drawn so far.
2566  unsigned int ElemCount; // 4 // Number of indices (multiple of 3) to be rendered as triangles. Vertices are stored in the callee ImDrawList's vtx_buffer[] array, indices in idx_buffer[].
2567  ImDrawCallback UserCallback; // 4-8 // If != NULL, call the function instead of rendering the vertices. clip_rect and texture_id will be set normally.
2568  void *UserCallbackData; // 4-8 // The draw callback code can access this.
2569 
2570  ImDrawCmd()
2571  {
2572  memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this));
2573  } // Also ensure our padding fields are zeroed
2574 
2575 // Since 1.83: returns ImTextureID associated with this draw call. Warning: DO NOT assume this is always same as 'TextureId' (we will change this function for an upcoming feature)
2576  inline ImTextureID GetTexID() const
2577  {
2578  return TextureId;
2579  }
2580 };

2582 // Vertex layout
2583 #ifndef IMGUI_OVERRIDE_DRAWVERT_STRUCT_LAYOUT
2584 struct ImDrawVert
2585 {
2586  ImVec2 pos;
2587  ImVec2 uv;
2588  ImU32 col;
2589 };
2590 #else
2591 // You can override the vertex format layout by defining IMGUI_OVERRIDE_DRAWVERT_STRUCT_LAYOUT in imconfig.h
2592 // The code expect ImVec2 pos (8 bytes), ImVec2 uv (8 bytes), ImU32 col (4 bytes), but you can re-order them or add other fields as needed to simplify integration in your engine.
2593 // The type has to be described within the macro (you can either declare the struct or use a typedef). This is because ImVec2/ImU32 are likely not declared a the time you'd want to set your type up.
2594 // NOTE: IMGUI DOESN'T CLEAR THE STRUCTURE AND DOESN'T CALL A CONSTRUCTOR SO ANY CUSTOM FIELD WILL BE UNINITIALIZED. IF YOU ADD EXTRA FIELDS (SUCH AS A 'Z' COORDINATES) YOU WILL NEED TO CLEAR THEM DURING RENDER OR TO IGNORE THEM.
2595 IMGUI_OVERRIDE_DRAWVERT_STRUCT_LAYOUT;
2596 #endif

2637  IMGUI_API void SetCurrentChannel(ImDrawList *draw_list, int channel_idx);
2638 };
2639 
2640 // Flags for ImDrawList functions
2641 // (Legacy: bit 0 must always correspond to ImDrawFlags_Closed to be backward compatible with old API using a bool. Bits 1..3 must be unused)
2642 enum ImDrawFlags_
2643 {
2644  ImDrawFlags_None = 0,
2645  ImDrawFlags_Closed = 1 << 0, // PathStroke(), AddPolyline(): specify that shape should be closed (Important: this is always == 1 for legacy reason)
2646  ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopLeft = 1 << 4, // AddRect(), AddRectFilled(), PathRect(): enable rounding top-left corner only (when rounding > 0.0f, we default to all corners). Was 0x01.
2647  ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopRight = 1 << 5, // AddRect(), AddRectFilled(), PathRect(): enable rounding top-right corner only (when rounding > 0.0f, we default to all corners). Was 0x02.
2648  ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomLeft = 1 << 6, // AddRect(), AddRectFilled(), PathRect(): enable rounding bottom-left corner only (when rounding > 0.0f, we default to all corners). Was 0x04.
2649  ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomRight = 1 << 7, // AddRect(), AddRectFilled(), PathRect(): enable rounding bottom-right corner only (when rounding > 0.0f, we default to all corners). Wax 0x08.
2650  ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersNone = 1 << 8, // AddRect(), AddRectFilled(), PathRect(): disable rounding on all corners (when rounding > 0.0f). This is NOT zero, NOT an implicit flag!
2651  ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTop = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopLeft | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopRight,
2652  ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottom = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomLeft | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomRight,
2653  ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersLeft = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomLeft | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopLeft,
2654  ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersRight = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomRight | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopRight,
2655  ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersAll = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopLeft | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopRight | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomLeft | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomRight,
2656  ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersDefault_ = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersAll, // Default to ALL corners if none of the _RoundCornersXX flags are specified.
2657  ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersMask_ = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersAll | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersNone
2658 };
2659 
2660 // Flags for ImDrawList instance. Those are set automatically by ImGui:: functions from ImGuiIO settings, and generally not manipulated directly.
2661 // It is however possible to temporarily alter flags between calls to ImDrawList:: functions.
2662 enum ImDrawListFlags_
2663 {
2664  ImDrawListFlags_None = 0,
2665  ImDrawListFlags_AntiAliasedLines = 1 << 0, // Enable anti-aliased lines/borders (*2 the number of triangles for 1.0f wide line or lines thin enough to be drawn using textures, otherwise *3 the number of triangles)
2666  ImDrawListFlags_AntiAliasedLinesUseTex = 1 << 1, // Enable anti-aliased lines/borders using textures when possible. Require backend to render with bilinear filtering.
2667  ImDrawListFlags_AntiAliasedFill = 1 << 2, // Enable anti-aliased edge around filled shapes (rounded rectangles, circles).
2668  ImDrawListFlags_AllowVtxOffset = 1 << 3 // Can emit 'VtxOffset > 0' to allow large meshes. Set when 'ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasVtxOffset' is enabled.
2669 };
2670 
2671 // Draw command list
2672 // This is the low-level list of polygons that ImGui:: functions are filling. At the end of the frame,
2673 // all command lists are passed to your ImGuiIO::RenderDrawListFn function for rendering.
2674 // Each dear imgui window contains its own ImDrawList. You can use ImGui::GetWindowDrawList() to
2675 // access the current window draw list and draw custom primitives.
2676 // You can interleave normal ImGui:: calls and adding primitives to the current draw list.
2677 // In single viewport mode, top-left is == GetMainViewport()->Pos (generally 0,0), bottom-right is == GetMainViewport()->Pos+Size (generally io.DisplaySize).
2678 // You are totally free to apply whatever transformation matrix to want to the data (depending on the use of the transformation you may want to apply it to ClipRect as well!)
2679 // Important: Primitives are always added to the list and not culled (culling is done at higher-level by ImGui:: functions), if you use this API a lot consider coarse culling your drawn objects.
2680 struct ImDrawList
2681 {
2682  // This is what you have to render
2683  ImVector<ImDrawCmd> CmdBuffer; // Draw commands. Typically 1 command = 1 GPU draw call, unless the command is a callback.
2684  ImVector<ImDrawIdx> IdxBuffer; // Index buffer. Each command consume ImDrawCmd::ElemCount of those
2685  ImVector<ImDrawVert> VtxBuffer; // Vertex buffer.
2686  ImDrawListFlags Flags; // Flags, you may poke into these to adjust anti-aliasing settings per-primitive.
2687 
2688  // [Internal, used while building lists]
2689  unsigned int _VtxCurrentIdx; // [Internal] generally == VtxBuffer.Size unless we are past 64K vertices, in which case this gets reset to 0.
2690  const ImDrawListSharedData *_Data; // Pointer to shared draw data (you can use ImGui::GetDrawListSharedData() to get the one from current ImGui context)
2691  const char *_OwnerName; // Pointer to owner window's name for debugging
2692  ImDrawVert *_VtxWritePtr; // [Internal] point within VtxBuffer.Data after each add command (to avoid using the ImVector<> operators too much)
2693  ImDrawIdx *_IdxWritePtr; // [Internal] point within IdxBuffer.Data after each add command (to avoid using the ImVector<> operators too much)
2694  ImVector<ImVec4> _ClipRectStack; // [Internal]
2695  ImVector<ImTextureID> _TextureIdStack; // [Internal]
2696  ImVector<ImVec2> _Path; // [Internal] current path building
2697  ImDrawCmdHeader _CmdHeader; // [Internal] template of active commands. Fields should match those of CmdBuffer.back().
2698  ImDrawListSplitter _Splitter; // [Internal] for channels api (note: prefer using your own persistent instance of ImDrawListSplitter!)
2699  float _FringeScale; // [Internal] anti-alias fringe is scaled by this value, this helps to keep things sharp while zooming at vertex buffer content
2700 
2701  // If you want to create ImDrawList instances, pass them ImGui::GetDrawListSharedData() or create and use your own ImDrawListSharedData (so you can use ImDrawList without ImGui)
2702  ImDrawList(const ImDrawListSharedData *shared_data)
2703  {
2704  memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this)); _Data = shared_data;
2705  }
2706 
2707  ~ImDrawList()
2708  {
2709  _ClearFreeMemory();
2710  }
2711  IMGUI_API void PushClipRect(ImVec2 clip_rect_min, ImVec2 clip_rect_max, bool intersect_with_current_clip_rect = false); // Render-level scissoring. This is passed down to your render function but not used for CPU-side coarse clipping. Prefer using higher-level ImGui::PushClipRect() to affect logic (hit-testing and widget culling)
2712  IMGUI_API void PushClipRectFullScreen();
2713  IMGUI_API void PopClipRect();
2714  IMGUI_API void PushTextureID(ImTextureID texture_id);
2715  IMGUI_API void PopTextureID();
2716  inline ImVec2 GetClipRectMin() const
2717  {
2718  const ImVec4 &cr = _ClipRectStack.back(); return ImVec2(cr.x, cr.y);
2719  }
2720  inline ImVec2 GetClipRectMax() const
2721  {
2722  const ImVec4 &cr = _ClipRectStack.back(); return ImVec2(cr.z, cr.w);
2723  }

2725  // Primitives

2727  // - For circle primitives, use "num_segments == 0" to automatically calculate tessellation (preferred).
2728  // In older versions (until Dear ImGui 1.77) the AddCircle functions defaulted to num_segments == 12.
2729  // In future versions we will use textures to provide cheaper and higher-quality circles.
2730  // Use AddNgon() and AddNgonFilled() functions if you need to guaranteed a specific number of sides.

2854 // All draw data to render a Dear ImGui frame
2855 // (NB: the style and the naming convention here is a little inconsistent, we currently preserve them for backward compatibility purpose,
2856 // as this is one of the oldest structure exposed by the library! Basically, ImDrawList == CmdList)
2857 struct ImDrawData
2858 {
2859  bool Valid; // Only valid after Render() is called and before the next NewFrame() is called.
2860  int CmdListsCount; // Number of ImDrawList* to render

2862  int TotalVtxCount; // For convenience, sum of all ImDrawList's VtxBuffer.Size
2863  ImDrawList **CmdLists; // Array of ImDrawList* to render. The ImDrawList are owned by ImGuiContext and only pointed to from here.
2864  ImVec2 DisplayPos; // Top-left position of the viewport to render (== top-left of the orthogonal projection matrix to use) (== GetMainViewport()->Pos for the main viewport, == (0.0) in most single-viewport applications)
2865  ImVec2 DisplaySize; // Size of the viewport to render (== GetMainViewport()->Size for the main viewport, == io.DisplaySize in most single-viewport applications)
2866  ImVec2 FramebufferScale; // Amount of pixels for each unit of DisplaySize. Based on io.DisplayFramebufferScale. Generally (1,1) on normal display, (2,2) on OSX with Retina display.
2867 
2868  // Functions
2869  ImDrawData()
2870  {
2871  Clear();
2872  }
2873  void Clear()
2874  {
2875  memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this));
2876  } // The ImDrawList are owned by ImGuiContext!
2877  IMGUI_API void DeIndexAllBuffers(); // Helper to convert all buffers from indexed to non-indexed, in case you cannot render indexed. Note: this is slow and most likely a waste of resources. Always prefer indexed rendering!
2878  IMGUI_API void ScaleClipRects(const ImVec2 &fb_scale); // Helper to scale the ClipRect field of each ImDrawCmd. Use if your final output buffer is at a different scale than Dear ImGui expects, or if there is a difference between your window resolution and framebuffer resolution.
2879 };

2884 
2885 struct ImFontConfig
2886 {
2887  void *FontData; // // TTF/OTF data
2888  int FontDataSize; // // TTF/OTF data size
2889  bool FontDataOwnedByAtlas; // true // TTF/OTF data ownership taken by the container ImFontAtlas (will delete memory itself).
2890  int FontNo; // 0 // Index of font within TTF/OTF file
2891  float SizePixels; // // Size in pixels for rasterizer (more or less maps to the resulting font height).
2892  int OversampleH; // 3 // Rasterize at higher quality for sub-pixel positioning. Note the difference between 2 and 3 is minimal so you can reduce this to 2 to save memory. Read https://github.com/nothings/stb/blob/master/tests/oversample/README.md for details.
2893  int OversampleV; // 1 // Rasterize at higher quality for sub-pixel positioning. This is not really useful as we don't use sub-pixel positions on the Y axis.
2894  bool PixelSnapH; // false // Align every glyph to pixel boundary. Useful e.g. if you are merging a non-pixel aligned font with the default font. If enabled, you can set OversampleH/V to 1.
2895  ImVec2 GlyphExtraSpacing; // 0, 0 // Extra spacing (in pixels) between glyphs. Only X axis is supported for now.
2896  ImVec2 GlyphOffset; // 0, 0 // Offset all glyphs from this font input.
2897  const ImWchar *GlyphRanges; // NULL // Pointer to a user-provided list of Unicode range (2 value per range, values are inclusive, zero-terminated list). THE ARRAY DATA NEEDS TO PERSIST AS LONG AS THE FONT IS ALIVE.
2898  float GlyphMinAdvanceX; // 0 // Minimum AdvanceX for glyphs, set Min to align font icons, set both Min/Max to enforce mono-space font
2899  float GlyphMaxAdvanceX; // FLT_MAX // Maximum AdvanceX for glyphs
2900  bool MergeMode; // false // Merge into previous ImFont, so you can combine multiple inputs font into one ImFont (e.g. ASCII font + icons + Japanese glyphs). You may want to use GlyphOffset.y when merge font of different heights.
2901  unsigned int FontBuilderFlags; // 0 // Settings for custom font builder. THIS IS BUILDER IMPLEMENTATION DEPENDENT. Leave as zero if unsure.
2902  float RasterizerMultiply; // 1.0f // Brighten (>1.0f) or darken (<1.0f) font output. Brightening small fonts may be a good workaround to make them more readable.
2903  ImWchar EllipsisChar; // -1 // Explicitly specify unicode codepoint of ellipsis character. When fonts are being merged first specified ellipsis will be used.
2904 
2905  // [Internal]
2906  char Name[40]; // Name (strictly to ease debugging)
2907  ImFont *DstFont;
2908 
2909  IMGUI_API ImFontConfig();
2910 };

2912 // Hold rendering data for one glyph.
2913 // (Note: some language parsers may fail to convert the 31+1 bitfield members, in this case maybe drop store a single u32 or we can rework this)
2914 struct ImFontGlyph
2915 {
2916  unsigned int Colored : 1; // Flag to indicate glyph is colored and should generally ignore tinting (make it usable with no shift on little-endian as this is used in loops)
2917  unsigned int Visible : 1; // Flag to indicate glyph has no visible pixels (e.g. space). Allow early out when rendering.
2918  unsigned int Codepoint : 30; // 0x0000..0x10FFFF
2919  float AdvanceX; // Distance to next character (= data from font + ImFontConfig::GlyphExtraSpacing.x baked in)
2920  float X0, Y0, X1, Y1; // Glyph corners
2921  float U0, V0, U1, V1; // Texture coordinates
2922 };
2923 
2924 // Helper to build glyph ranges from text/string data. Feed your application strings/characters to it then call BuildRanges().
2925 // This is essentially a tightly packed of vector of 64k booleans = 8KB storage.
2926 struct ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder
2927 {
2928  ImVector<ImU32> UsedChars; // Store 1-bit per Unicode code point (0=unused, 1=used)
2929 
2930  ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder()
2931  {
2932  Clear();
2933  }
2934  inline void Clear()
2935  {
2936  int size_in_bytes = (IM_UNICODE_CODEPOINT_MAX + 1) / 8; UsedChars.resize(size_in_bytes / (int)sizeof(ImU32)); memset(UsedChars.Data, 0, (size_t)size_in_bytes);
2937  }
2938  inline bool GetBit(size_t n) const
2939  {
2940  int off = (int)(n >> 5); ImU32 mask = 1u << (n & 31); return (UsedChars[off] & mask) != 0;
2941  } // Get bit n in the array
2942  inline void SetBit(size_t n)
2943  {
2944  int off = (int)(n >> 5); ImU32 mask = 1u << (n & 31); UsedChars[off] |= mask;
2945  } // Set bit n in the array
2946  inline void AddChar(ImWchar c)
2947  {
2948  SetBit(c);
2949  } // Add character
2950  IMGUI_API void AddText(const char *text, const char *text_end = NULL); // Add string (each character of the UTF-8 string are added)
2951  IMGUI_API void AddRanges(const ImWchar *ranges); // Add ranges, e.g. builder.AddRanges(ImFontAtlas::GetGlyphRangesDefault()) to force add all of ASCII/Latin+Ext
2952  IMGUI_API void BuildRanges(ImVector<ImWchar> *out_ranges); // Output new ranges
2953 };
2954 
2955 // See ImFontAtlas::AddCustomRectXXX functions.
2956 struct ImFontAtlasCustomRect
2957 {
2958  unsigned short Width, Height; // Input // Desired rectangle dimension
2959  unsigned short X, Y; // Output // Packed position in Atlas
2960  unsigned int GlyphID; // Input // For custom font glyphs only (ID < 0x110000)
2961  float GlyphAdvanceX; // Input // For custom font glyphs only: glyph xadvance
2962  ImVec2 GlyphOffset; // Input // For custom font glyphs only: glyph display offset
2963  ImFont *Font; // Input // For custom font glyphs only: target font
2964  ImFontAtlasCustomRect()
2965  {
2966  Width = Height = 0; X = Y = 0xFFFF; GlyphID = 0; GlyphAdvanceX = 0.0f; GlyphOffset = ImVec2(0, 0); Font = NULL;
2967  }
2968  bool IsPacked() const
2969  {
2970  return X != 0xFFFF;
2971  }
2972 };
2973 
2974 // Flags for ImFontAtlas build
2975 enum ImFontAtlasFlags_
2976 {
2977  ImFontAtlasFlags_None = 0,
2978  ImFontAtlasFlags_NoPowerOfTwoHeight = 1 << 0, // Don't round the height to next power of two
2979  ImFontAtlasFlags_NoMouseCursors = 1 << 1, // Don't build software mouse cursors into the atlas (save a little texture memory)
2980  ImFontAtlasFlags_NoBakedLines = 1 << 2 // Don't build thick line textures into the atlas (save a little texture memory). The AntiAliasedLinesUseTex features uses them, otherwise they will be rendered using polygons (more expensive for CPU/GPU).
2981 };
2982 
2983 // Load and rasterize multiple TTF/OTF fonts into a same texture. The font atlas will build a single texture holding:
2984 // - One or more fonts.
2985 // - Custom graphics data needed to render the shapes needed by Dear ImGui.
2986 // - Mouse cursor shapes for software cursor rendering (unless setting 'Flags |= ImFontAtlasFlags_NoMouseCursors' in the font atlas).
2987 // It is the user-code responsibility to setup/build the atlas, then upload the pixel data into a texture accessible by your graphics api.
2988 // - Optionally, call any of the AddFont*** functions. If you don't call any, the default font embedded in the code will be loaded for you.
2989 // - Call GetTexDataAsAlpha8() or GetTexDataAsRGBA32() to build and retrieve pixels data.
2990 // - Upload the pixels data into a texture within your graphics system (see imgui_impl_xxxx.cpp examples)
2991 // - Call SetTexID(my_tex_id); and pass the pointer/identifier to your texture in a format natural to your graphics API.
2992 // This value will be passed back to you during rendering to identify the texture. Read FAQ entry about ImTextureID for more details.
2993 // Common pitfalls:
2994 // - If you pass a 'glyph_ranges' array to AddFont*** functions, you need to make sure that your array persist up until the
2995 // atlas is build (when calling GetTexData*** or Build()). We only copy the pointer, not the data.
2996 // - Important: By default, AddFontFromMemoryTTF() takes ownership of the data. Even though we are not writing to it, we will free the pointer on destruction.
2997 // You can set font_cfg->FontDataOwnedByAtlas=false to keep ownership of your data and it won't be freed,
2998 // - Even though many functions are suffixed with "TTF", OTF data is supported just as well.
2999 // - This is an old API and it is currently awkward for those and and various other reasons! We will address them in the future!
3000 struct ImFontAtlas
3001 {
3002  IMGUI_API ImFontAtlas();
3003  IMGUI_API ~ImFontAtlas();
3004  IMGUI_API ImFont *AddFont(const ImFontConfig *font_cfg);
3005  IMGUI_API ImFont *AddFontDefault(const ImFontConfig *font_cfg = NULL);
3006  IMGUI_API ImFont *AddFontFromFileTTF(const char *filename, float size_pixels, const ImFontConfig *font_cfg = NULL, const ImWchar *glyph_ranges = NULL);
3007  IMGUI_API ImFont *AddFontFromMemoryTTF(void *font_data, int font_size, float size_pixels, const ImFontConfig *font_cfg = NULL, const ImWchar *glyph_ranges = NULL); // Note: Transfer ownership of 'ttf_data' to ImFontAtlas! Will be deleted after destruction of the atlas. Set font_cfg->FontDataOwnedByAtlas=false to keep ownership of your data and it won't be freed.
3008  IMGUI_API ImFont *AddFontFromMemoryCompressedTTF(const void *compressed_font_data, int compressed_font_size, float size_pixels, const ImFontConfig *font_cfg = NULL, const ImWchar *glyph_ranges = NULL); // 'compressed_font_data' still owned by caller. Compress with binary_to_compressed_c.cpp.
3009  IMGUI_API ImFont *AddFontFromMemoryCompressedBase85TTF(const char *compressed_font_data_base85, float size_pixels, const ImFontConfig *font_cfg = NULL, const ImWchar *glyph_ranges = NULL); // 'compressed_font_data_base85' still owned by caller. Compress with binary_to_compressed_c.cpp with -base85 parameter.
3010  IMGUI_API void ClearInputData(); // Clear input data (all ImFontConfig structures including sizes, TTF data, glyph ranges, etc.) = all the data used to build the texture and fonts.
3011  IMGUI_API void ClearTexData(); // Clear output texture data (CPU side). Saves RAM once the texture has been copied to graphics memory.
3012  IMGUI_API void ClearFonts(); // Clear output font data (glyphs storage, UV coordinates).
3013  IMGUI_API void Clear(); // Clear all input and output.
3014 
3015  // Build atlas, retrieve pixel data.
3016  // User is in charge of copying the pixels into graphics memory (e.g. create a texture with your engine). Then store your texture handle with SetTexID().
3017  // The pitch is always = Width * BytesPerPixels (1 or 4)
3018  // Building in RGBA32 format is provided for convenience and compatibility, but note that unless you manually manipulate or copy color data into
3019  // the texture (e.g. when using the AddCustomRect*** api), then the RGB pixels emitted will always be white (~75% of memory/bandwidth waste.
3020  IMGUI_API bool Build(); // Build pixels data. This is called automatically for you by the GetTexData*** functions.
3021  IMGUI_API void GetTexDataAsAlpha8(unsigned char **out_pixels, int *out_width, int *out_height, int *out_bytes_per_pixel = NULL); // 1 byte per-pixel
3022  IMGUI_API void GetTexDataAsRGBA32(unsigned char **out_pixels, int *out_width, int *out_height, int *out_bytes_per_pixel = NULL); // 4 bytes-per-pixel
3023  bool IsBuilt() const
3024  {
3025  return Fonts.Size > 0 && TexReady;
3026  } // Bit ambiguous: used to detect when user didn't built texture but effectively we should check TexID != 0 except that would be backend dependent...
3027  void SetTexID(ImTextureID id)
3028  {
3029  TexID = id;
3030  }
3031

3033  // Glyph Ranges
3034  //-------------------------------------------
3035 
3036  // Helpers to retrieve list of common Unicode ranges (2 value per range, values are inclusive, zero-terminated list)
3037  // NB: Make sure that your string are UTF-8 and NOT in your local code page. In C++11, you can create UTF-8 string literal using the u8"Hello world" syntax. See FAQ for details.
3038  // NB: Consider using ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder to build glyph ranges from textual data.
3039  IMGUI_API const ImWchar *GetGlyphRangesDefault(); // Basic Latin, Extended Latin
3040  IMGUI_API const ImWchar *GetGlyphRangesKorean(); // Default + Korean characters
3041  IMGUI_API const ImWchar *GetGlyphRangesJapanese(); // Default + Hiragana, Katakana, Half-Width, Selection of 2999 Ideographs
3042  IMGUI_API const ImWchar *GetGlyphRangesChineseFull(); // Default + Half-Width + Japanese Hiragana/Katakana + full set of about 21000 CJK Unified Ideographs
3043  IMGUI_API const ImWchar *GetGlyphRangesChineseSimplifiedCommon();// Default + Half-Width + Japanese Hiragana/Katakana + set of 2500 CJK Unified Ideographs for common simplified Chinese
3044  IMGUI_API const ImWchar *GetGlyphRangesCyrillic(); // Default + about 400 Cyrillic characters
3045  IMGUI_API const ImWchar *GetGlyphRangesThai(); // Default + Thai characters

3049  // [BETA] Custom Rectangles/Glyphs API
3050  //-------------------------------------------
3051 
3052  // You can request arbitrary rectangles to be packed into the atlas, for your own purposes.
3053  // - After calling Build(), you can query the rectangle position and render your pixels.
3054  // - If you render colored output, set 'atlas->TexPixelsUseColors = true' as this may help some backends decide of prefered texture format.
3055  // - You can also request your rectangles to be mapped as font glyph (given a font + Unicode point),
3056  // so you can render e.g. custom colorful icons and use them as regular glyphs.
3057  // - Read docs/FONTS.md for more details about using colorful icons.
3058  // - Note: this API may be redesigned later in order to support multi-monitor varying DPI settings.
3059  IMGUI_API int AddCustomRectRegular(int width, int height);
3060  IMGUI_API int AddCustomRectFontGlyph(ImFont *font, ImWchar id, int width, int height, float advance_x, const ImVec2 &offset = ImVec2(0, 0));
3061  ImFontAtlasCustomRect *GetCustomRectByIndex(int index)
3062  {
3063  IM_ASSERT(index >= 0); return &CustomRects[index];
3064  }

3068  IMGUI_API bool GetMouseCursorTexData(ImGuiMouseCursor cursor, ImVec2 *out_offset, ImVec2 *out_size, ImVec2 out_uv_border[2], ImVec2 out_uv_fill[2]);

3073 
3074  ImFontAtlasFlags Flags; // Build flags (see ImFontAtlasFlags_)
3075  ImTextureID TexID; // User data to refer to the texture once it has been uploaded to user's graphic systems. It is passed back to you during rendering via the ImDrawCmd structure.
3076  int TexDesiredWidth; // Texture width desired by user before Build(). Must be a power-of-two. If have many glyphs your graphics API have texture size restrictions you may want to increase texture width to decrease height.
3077  int TexGlyphPadding; // Padding between glyphs within texture in pixels. Defaults to 1. If your rendering method doesn't rely on bilinear filtering you may set this to 0.
3078  bool Locked; // Marked as Locked by ImGui::NewFrame() so attempt to modify the atlas will assert.

3081  // NB: Access texture data via GetTexData*() calls! Which will setup a default font for you.

3083  bool TexPixelsUseColors; // Tell whether our texture data is known to use colors (rather than just alpha channel), in order to help backend select a format.
3084  unsigned char *TexPixelsAlpha8; // 1 component per pixel, each component is unsigned 8-bit. Total size = TexWidth * TexHeight
3085  unsigned int *TexPixelsRGBA32; // 4 component per pixel, each component is unsigned 8-bit. Total size = TexWidth * TexHeight * 4

3109 // Font runtime data and rendering
3110 // ImFontAtlas automatically loads a default embedded font for you when you call GetTexDataAsAlpha8() or GetTexDataAsRGBA32().
3111 struct ImFont
3112 {
3113  // Members: Hot ~20/24 bytes (for CalcTextSize)
3114  ImVector<float> IndexAdvanceX; // 12-16 // out // // Sparse. Glyphs->AdvanceX in a directly indexable way (cache-friendly for CalcTextSize functions which only this this info, and are often bottleneck in large UI).
3115  float FallbackAdvanceX; // 4 // out // = FallbackGlyph->AdvanceX
3116  float FontSize; // 4 // in // // Height of characters/line, set during loading (don't change after loading)
3117 
3118  // Members: Hot ~28/40 bytes (for CalcTextSize + render loop)
3119  ImVector<ImWchar> IndexLookup; // 12-16 // out // // Sparse. Index glyphs by Unicode code-point.
3120  ImVector<ImFontGlyph> Glyphs; // 12-16 // out // // All glyphs.
3121  const ImFontGlyph *FallbackGlyph; // 4-8 // out // = FindGlyph(FontFallbackChar)
3122 
3123  // Members: Cold ~32/40 bytes
3124  ImFontAtlas *ContainerAtlas; // 4-8 // out // // What we has been loaded into
3125  const ImFontConfig *ConfigData; // 4-8 // in // // Pointer within ContainerAtlas->ConfigData
3126  short ConfigDataCount; // 2 // in // ~ 1 // Number of ImFontConfig involved in creating this font. Bigger than 1 when merging multiple font sources into one ImFont.
3127  ImWchar FallbackChar; // 2 // out // = FFFD/'?' // Character used if a glyph isn't found.
3128  ImWchar EllipsisChar; // 2 // out // = '...' // Character used for ellipsis rendering.
3129  ImWchar DotChar; // 2 // out // = '.' // Character used for ellipsis rendering (if a single '...' character isn't found)
3130  bool DirtyLookupTables; // 1 // out //
3131  float Scale; // 4 // in // = 1.f // Base font scale, multiplied by the per-window font scale which you can adjust with SetWindowFontScale()
3132  float Ascent, Descent; // 4+4 // out // // Ascent: distance from top to bottom of e.g. 'A' [0..FontSize]
3133  int MetricsTotalSurface;// 4 // out // // Total surface in pixels to get an idea of the font rasterization/texture cost (not exact, we approximate the cost of padding between glyphs)
3134  ImU8 Used4kPagesMap[(IM_UNICODE_CODEPOINT_MAX + 1) / 4096 / 8]; // 2 bytes if ImWchar=ImWchar16, 34 bytes if ImWchar==ImWchar32. Store 1-bit for each block of 4K codepoints that has one active glyph. This is mainly used to facilitate iterations across all used codepoints.
3135

3138  IMGUI_API ~ImFont();
3139  IMGUI_API const ImFontGlyph *FindGlyph(ImWchar c) const;

3175 // Flags stored in ImGuiViewport::Flags, giving indications to the platform backends.
3176 enum ImGuiViewportFlags_
3177 {
3178  ImGuiViewportFlags_None = 0,
3179  ImGuiViewportFlags_IsPlatformWindow = 1 << 0, // Represent a Platform Window
3180  ImGuiViewportFlags_IsPlatformMonitor = 1 << 1, // Represent a Platform Monitor (unused yet)
3181  ImGuiViewportFlags_OwnedByApp = 1 << 2 // Platform Window: is created/managed by the application (rather than a dear imgui backend)

3183 
3184 // - Currently represents the Platform Window created by the application which is hosting our Dear ImGui windows.
3185 // - In 'docking' branch with multi-viewport enabled, we extend this concept to have multiple active viewports.
3186 // - In the future we will extend this concept further to also represent Platform Monitor and support a "no main platform window" operation mode.
3187 // - About Main Area vs Work Area:
3188 // - Main Area = entire viewport.
3189 // - Work Area = entire viewport minus sections used by main menu bars (for platform windows), or by task bar (for platform monitor).
3190 // - Windows are generally trying to stay within the Work Area of their host viewport.
3191 struct ImGuiViewport
3192 {
3193  ImGuiViewportFlags Flags; // See ImGuiViewportFlags_
3194  ImVec2 Pos; // Main Area: Position of the viewport (Dear ImGui coordinates are the same as OS desktop/native coordinates)
3195  ImVec2 Size; // Main Area: Size of the viewport.
3196  ImVec2 WorkPos; // Work Area: Position of the viewport minus task bars, menus bars, status bars (>= Pos)
3197  ImVec2 WorkSize; // Work Area: Size of the viewport minus task bars, menu bars, status bars (<= Size)
3198 
3199  ImGuiViewport()
3200  {
3201  memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this));
3202  }
3203 
3204  // Helpers
3205  ImVec2 GetCenter() const
3206  {
3207  return ImVec2(Pos.x + Size.x * 0.5f, Pos.y + Size.y * 0.5f);
3208  }
3209  ImVec2 GetWorkCenter() const
3210  {
3211  return ImVec2(WorkPos.x + WorkSize.x * 0.5f, WorkPos.y + WorkSize.y * 0.5f);
3212  }
3213 };
